<title>Daily Commentary - December 23, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 23, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Here's a strange way to celebrate Christmas week.  A federal
judge in New York has ruled that military stores must again start
selling <I>Penthouse</I> and other skin magazines.  The order
is temporary, but I'm afraid the arrogance of our federal judges
is permanent.

<p>

Earlier this year, the Congress, after endless pleas from
service women and military families, finally banned porn sales
at PX's worldwide.  Over the years, the Pentagon had resisted
the ban.  Not only will boys be boys, the Defense Department said,
but they must be boys on the government's dime at government stores.
It's an absurd argument, which is one reason why Congress easily
passed the ban and President Clinton signed it into law.

<p>

But the Clinton administration is reverting to old ways.
It now says that even though the judge's order is technically
local, it will apply it to military stores worldwide.  So, Christmas
week will come with the porn magazines in stock, right between
the holly and the ivy.  It's just one more lump of coal from our
radical federal courts.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

