<title>Daily Commentary - December 20, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 20, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

You know and I know that Americans will file lawsuits over
almost everything.  Some of the lawsuits involving our schools
prove that point beyond all doubt.  In a case that went all the
way to the Supreme Court, a New York school system failed in its
attempt to require that a high school Bible club -- now get this
-- include non-Christians among its officers.  The Club members
are overjoyed.  Now they can pursue their mission, which is to
bring together young people who believe that the Bible is the
inspired word of God.

<p>

The school system thought that any such requirement was bound
to be unconstitutional.  They were joined by the usual suspects,
including the left-wing group, People for the American Way.  They
suggested that allowing Christians to meet on their own terms
somehow violates the separation of church and state.  It seems
to me that the opposite is what's obviously true.  A school that
will not allow a student Bible club to define its by-laws is clearly
interfering with those students' fundamental religious freedom.

<p>

Our Supreme Court has now sided with the students.  For once,
the High Court has done the right thing.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

