<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 18, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 18, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Our oldest daughter Elyse is home for the holidays.  She attends
William and Mary College and, from what I can tell, is getting
an excellent education.  At least her mother and I hope so.

<p>

But each passing day brings more signs that all's not well
in higher education.  For one thing, college after college is
expelling a man named William Shakespeare.  Old Bill has no peer
among English poets and playwrights, but it seems our campuses
are still bent on tossing him overboard.  A new report says that
only 23 of the nation's 70 leading universities require English
majors to read Shakespeare.  Even more worrisome is what's replacing
him.  At one college, it's gangster movies.  At others it is courses
on AIDS activism, carnivals, CD-ROMs, homophobia, Madonna, the
socialist struggle and, believe it or not, theme parks.

<p>

Let me say the obvious.  Parents scrimp and save to send
their children to college, so they can lift themselves higher
on the ladder of knowledge.  Instead, many colleges are offering
courses no high school would have dared offer 20 years ago.  That,
as William Shakespeare would put it, is a tragedy.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

<center><b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwold.html.cgi#current">Last Month's Commentaries</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/radio/wwdaily.html.cgi#current">This Month's Commentaries</a>]
</b></center>

<p>

