<html>

<title>Daily Commentary - December 16, 1996</title>

<body>

<center><h1>Daily Commentary<br>
December 16, 1996</h1></center>

<p><hr width=75% size=3><p>

I'm Gary Bauer for Washington Watch.

<p>

Bill Clinton gave a speech the other day, and it reminded
me of one of the first principles of modern politics.  The President
used some of the same rhetoric that he employed so successfully
during the campaign.  He declared himself &quot;for&quot; a long
list of mainstream values:  stronger families, leaner government,
crackdowns on criminals, welfare reform, and a balanced budget.
Who can argue with that?  With politicians of every stripe embracing
these ideas, why is it our society seems to slip ever further
away from them?

<p>

The answer is simple.  In politics, watch what our leaders
do, not what they say.  Let me repeat that -- watch what they
do, not only what they say.  If it's the president, watch his
appointments to the federal bench and to the Cabinet.  If it's
the Congress, watch the people they regularly confirm for the
courts.

<p>

Today, when nearly everyone styles himself as &quot;pro-family,&quot; 
it's even more essential than ever to keep ours eyes fixed
on the bottom line.  Let's make 1997 the year of pro-family deeds,
not just words.

<p>

For the Family Research Council, this is Gary Bauer with
today's Washington Watch.  For more information about us, call
1-800-225-4008.  That number again:  1-800-225-4008.

<p>

