<HEAD>



<TITLE>Tax Tips</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<center>
<img src = "/NTU/graphics_imaps/tipsban2.gif">
<p>
</center>
<br>

<center>
<h2>Choosing the Right Tax Advisor</h2>
</center>
<p>
<br>
<font size="+2">A</font>fter surviving the horror of yet another tax season, many people — daunted by 
the prospects of repeating the same performance next April 15 — resolve finally to put 
their personal finances in order.  But some drag their feet, because they don’t realize how 
much help experts like accounts and tax attorneys can provide.  Other people don’t know 
where to turn for professional guidance.

	<p>One woman, the president of a New York City-based management consulting 
firm, stated the problem succinctly: "I didn't think I was taking advantage of all the tax 
breaks I was entitled to.  And I wanted someone to show me how to make money on my 
money, instead of just paying over half to the government.”"

	<p>Like many people, she eventually found her accountant through referrals from 
friends and business associates.  She interviewed about five CPA's before making a final 
selection, and chose her current accountant because "he works with a lot of people at 
about my income level who own small businesses.”" In addition, she felt "the chemistry 
was right.”"

	<p>This woman's organized selection process can serve as a model for people in the 
market for accountants and tax lawyers.

	<p>CPA's provide a variety of services, from tax return preparation to financial 
planning to bookkeeping.  So before you begin shopping around for a practitioner, ask 
yourself this question:  What do I want an accountant to do for me?

	<p>If you need help organizing your personal finances, an accountant should be able 
to advise you on whether to rent or purchase a home, how much life and property 
insurance you need, and how to structure your investment portfolio, in addition to telling 
you how to pay a minimum amount of income tax.

	<p>As a generalist, a CPA can help you select specialists in narrower fields.  For 
example, he will work with attorneys, to help draft wills and trust agreements, and to put 
an estate plan into effect.  He will also work with stockbrokers, to help design a portfolio 
that makes the most of taxwise investments like tax-exempt mutual funds.

	<p>Do you need an accountant to prepare your tax return?  While some people can't 
justify the fee and prefer to follow the IRS instructions themselves, others take a different 
view.  A good accountant sees planning opportunities in the data gathered for a return.  
Looking over Schedule D, which lists securities transactions, an accountant might 
recommend donating highly appreciated securities as a way to maximize charitable 
deductions.

	<p>Look for someone who has sound business judgment as well as technical 
expertise.  And seek out a professional who offers tax planning advice throughout the 
year, not just at tax time.

	<p>Doctors, lawyers, small business owners and others with specialized needs are 
well advised to seek out accountants with experience and technical expertise in their 
particular areas.  Problems tend to repeat themselves, and accountants who specialize 
tend to keep current with the latest developments in their fields.

	<p>Expect to pay from $150 to $1,000 or more when an accountant prepares your tax 
return.  For consultation and planning, CPA's generally charge hourly rates.  Tax 
preparation fees may be deductible.  Consultation fees may also be deductible, depending 
on the service.

	<p>Tax lawyers are more expensive -- they generally charge higher hourly fees.  But 
they can save money for taxpayers with unusually complicated tax situations, for 
example, someone who has overlap between his complex business and personal tax 
matters.

	<p>Some people hire tax lawyers for advice in connection with a particular situation:  
to handle a divorce, to prepare an estate plan or to represent them in an IRS dispute.  
Select a tax attorney on the same basis as you choose an accountant -- by reputation and 
recommendation, with an eye to particular specialities.

	<p>Advisors who are both CPA's and attorneys can offer one-stop shopping.  They 
can work out an estate plan, for instance, and then draft the will and the trust agreements 
needed to carry out the plan.

	<h3>How to Conduct the Interview.</h3>
<p>
	Like most professionals, accountants and tax lawyers are best found through 
recommendations.  As you gather names, ask your friends and business associates exactly 
what they like—and don’n't like—about their advisors.  Find out whether they are easily 
accessible and whether they return telephone calls quickly.  Most advisors don't charge 
for an initial interview.  When you go in for the interview, ask these questions:
<p>
<ul>
•	<li>How do you determine fees?
	(When the advisor charges an hourly rate, ask for a time estimate for the 
	job.)

•	<p><li>What exactly will you do for the money?

•	<p><li>How much time will you spend with me, doing planning and 
consultation?

•	<p><li>Are you available only during tax season, or will you work with me 
	throughout the year?

•	<p><li>Who will actually handle the work, you or your assistant?  (If an 
associate will be responsible for your account, make sure to find out 
his qualifications and his fee schedule.  Will you feel comfortable 
working with him?)

•	<p><li>What are your areas of expertise?

•	<p><li>How will you keep me up to date on the latest tax developments?

•	<p><li>Does your office have microcomputer capabilities?  (Some advisors can 
do time-consuming “what if” planning with computer programs that 
instantly give them the results of a large number of hypothetical tax 
scenarios.)
</ul>

<p>
<br>
<p>
