<title>Legislative Hotline</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.gif"></center>

<p>

The Family Research Council has implemented a Legislative Hotline.  By dialing
<b>1-202-783-HOME</b>, you will access current information on pending family
issues in Washington, D.C., via telephone.  The hotline is updated every 
Friday evening.

<p>

Just in case you missed it, make sure to read 
<a href="/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotlnold.html">last week's message</a> so that 
you can stay current on the latest issues that affect you and your family.

<p>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/images/redline.gif"></center>
<p>

<center><h2>This Week's Message (December 6)</h2></center>

<p>

Welcome to the FRC information line.  Please note FRC's new address!
Our phone and fax numbers remain the same.  This message will
continue to be updated periodically until the 105th Congress reconvenes
in January.

<p>

As President Clinton announces some of his <a href="#cabinet">Cabinet 
appointments</a>, an Hawaii court hands down a decision on 
<a href="#homosexual">homosexual &quot;marriage,&quot;</a>
and the House and Senate organize for the <a href="#105">105th 
Congress</a>.

<p><a name="homosexual">

<h3>Issue One: Hawaii's Judicial Decision on Homosexual 
&quot;Marriage.&quot;</h3>

<p>

In a major setback for traditional marriage in Hawaii, Judge
Kevin Chang ruled on December 3 that the state constitution requires
the recognition of same-sex &quot;marriage,&quot; or homosexual
&quot;marriage.&quot;  The judge based his decision on the argument
that the couples' <I>gender</I> was the cause for being refused
a marriage license.  Of course, the homosexual movement sees this
as a breakthrough in gaining equal status and gaining benefits
previously only given to traditional married couples, such as
tax and health insurance benefits.  Robert Knight, FRC's Director
of Cultural Studies denounced the court decision saying, &quot;In
striking down Hawaii's state law that preserves marriage as the
union of one man and one woman, Judge Kevin Chang has ignored
the wisdom of the ages, the will of the Hawaiian people, and ample
evidence of the state's compelling interest in preserving this
vital institution.  This decision underscores Congress' wisdom
in enacting the Defense of Marriage Act, which protects other
states from the Hawaiian courts' reckless activism.&quot;  Knight
calls on &quot;Americans to examine and to exercise ways to nullify
the actions of judges who flout the law.  This is no small legal
matter but an assault on morality and the rule of law itself.
Hawaiians can assist the entire nation by ending the judicial
arrogance that has precipitated this national threat to marriage.&quot;
The case will be appealed to the Hawaiian Supreme Court, and
in the meantime, no state &quot;marriage&quot; licenses for homosexual
couples will be issued.  Many legal analysts expect the State
Supreme Court to decide this case in the spring of 1997 and most
observers expect the Court to uphold Judge Chang's decision.
Homosexual couples &quot;married&quot; in Hawaii are then expected
to seek recognition of these unions by other states, if Judge
Chang's decision is upheld.  Homosexual activists are also expected
to file legal challenges to the Defense of Marriage Act, which
was enacted during the recently completed session of Congress.

<p><a name="105">

<h3>Issue Two: House and Senate Leadership and Committees for the 105th 
Congress.</h3>

<p>

In the House and Senate, both Democrats and Republicans have
largely re-elected their current leadership and made committee
assignments for the new 105th Congress, which convenes January
7, 1997.  In the House, Newt Gingrich was renominated Speaker
of the House;  Dick Armey for Majority Leader; and Tom DeLay for
Majority Whip.  Senate Republicans renominated Trent Lott of Mississippi
as the Majority Leader; Don Nickles (Okla.) Majority Whip; Connie
Mack (Fla.) as Conference Chairman; and Paul Coverdell (Ga.) as
Conference Secretary. FRC takes note that several new and current
pro-family Senators were assigned to key Senate Committees.  Senators
Lauch Faircloth (Ga.) and Larry Craig (Idaho) were assigned to
the powerful Appropriations Committee.  Pro-life Senator John
Ashcroft (Mo.) and Sen.-elect Jeff Sessions (Ala.) were assigned
to the Judiciary Committee, which is responsible for reviewing
federal judicial nominees.  In the House, pro-life Rep. Bob Livingston
remains chairman of the powerful Appropriations Committee, and
two pro-life Representatives-elect were added:  Anne Northup (Ky.)
and Robert Aderholt (Ala.).  However, abortion rights leaders
Rosa DeLauro (D-Conn.) and Barbara Boxer (D-Calif.) will also
join the House and Senate Appropriations Committees, respectively.
Pro-life champion Henry Hyde (Ill.) remains chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee and four newly elected pro-life members were
added:  William Jenkins (Tenn.), Asa Hutchinson (Ark.), Ed Pease
(Ind.) and Chris Cannon of Utah.  Pro-life Rep. Charles Canady
will remain the chairman of the Constitution subcommittee, which
has jurisdiction over the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act, religious
freedom, parental rights and other key family issues.

<p><a name="cabinet">

<h3>Issue Three: New Liberal Clinton Cabinet Nominees.</h3>

<p>

On Thursday December 5th, President Clinton announced some of his top 
Cabinet nominees that would lead our national defense policy team.  Among 
his selections for these top positions are Madeline Albright, former US 
Ambassador to the UN, and retiring Senator Bill Cohen (R-ME).  Although both
of these individuals are aptly qualified, well-liked and respected
for their foreign policy knowledge and experience, both nominees
are considered to be cultural liberals.  Senator Cohen's appointment
as Secretary of Defense appears to be a gesture towards the moderate
and liberal Republicans in Congress at a time when the power between
the two parties is almost evenly divided.  Senator Cohen has
served a distinguished career in the U.S. Senate, however, he
has a record of consistently supporting federal funding of abortion
and even voted against the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.  He
tends to support the homosexual rights agenda -- Sen. Cohen is
a supporter of legally recognized &quot;domestic partnerships&quot;
and the Employment Non-Discrimination Act (ENDA), which would
elevate 'sexual orientation' to a specially protected status in
the area of employment.

<p>

Madeline Albright, President Clinton's recommended Secretary of
State, is a distinguished leader in foreign policy as demonstrated
during her tenure as U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations.  Yet,
in the midst of her broad background in foreign policy, her record
on cultural issues tends to be quite liberal.  As the leader of
the U.S. delegation to the Beijing Women's Conference, Albright
promised &quot;to see that American views and values are well
represented,&quot; however, the &quot;views and values&quot; which
she represented at the Conference were very much in line with
those advocated by western feminists -- an emphasis on &quot;reproductive
rights&quot; (i.e., abortion and unlimited contraceptive availability),
&quot;gender equality&quot; and the mainstreaming of a &quot;gender
perspective.&quot;  Although Ambassador Albright has expressed
opposition to forced abortions in China and religious persecution,
she has not backed any economic sanctions that would pressure
China to reform their human rights policies.

<p>

Thank you for calling the FRC Legislative Hotline.

<p>
