<br>
<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>January 8, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>



 


	In 1899 a baby girl was born to a poor family in China. Three previous children had died in infancy, and the family hoped for a boy. The midwife expected that the baby would be exposed to die as was customary, but the father allowed the girl to live and gave her an education. Jeanette Li became an educator and had a long and productive life, amply justifying her father's decision. She also had a son. Min Chu Li became a physician and obtained a position at the National Cancer Institute, where he showed that the drug methotrexate caused complete disappearance of choriocarcinoma, a rare but fatal tumor occurring in young women. This was the first demonstration that chemotherapy could cure metastatic cancer, as well as the first demonstration that widely disseminated cancer could be cured by any means.
<P>
	Abortion and infanticide have been discussed from many viewpoints, but often with the tacit assumption that potential or nascent human beings are interchangeable: the fetus aborted today can be fully replaced by a baby born later. One need not be a geneticist, or a theologian, to know that this is not so. Jeanette Li's father, an uneducated peasant, knew it. Overpopulation and unwanted pregnancy are real problems; lofty pronouncements cannot solve them. But it is equally unrealistic to assume that human beings, even potential or nascent ones, are as replaceable, and hence disposable, as automobile parts.
<P>
						David C. Stolinsky MD
						Los Angeles, Calif.
<P>
 [Note: The above letter with references was submitted to eight medical and scientific journals, including the <I>Journal of the National Cancer Institute</I>, where Dr. Li worked. All rejected it.]


</blockquote>


