<A NAME="april"><HR>

From: Eagle Forum (eagle@accessus.net)<br>
Date: Tue, 16 Apr 1996 09:49:53 -0500<BR>
Subject: C-NEWS: April Education Reporter [8 of 8]<P>

Education Briefs<P>
          Goals 2000 legislation may not be completely voluntary<BR>
          for the states after all. When Alabama Governor Fob<BR>
          James announced he would return the state's share of<BR>
          Goals 2000 funding ($6.6 million) and cease all<BR>
          participation in it, U.S. Education Secretary Richard<BR>
          Riley replied that dropping out is allowed only "if the<BR>
          appropriate authorities so decide." Riley has<BR>
          determined that the unelected State Superintendent<BR>
          Edward Richardson, who is "actively considering"<BR>
          spending the money, rather than Governor James,<BR>
          possesses the proper authority to make the decision <BR>
          to reject the funds.<P>

          Alabama Governor Fob James sent 800 copies of <BR>
          Darwin on Trial by Phillip Johnson to all the state's <BR>
          science teachers as a scientific counterbalance to<BR>
          controversial biology textbooks. The Alabama Course <BR>
          of Study for Science now requires that explanations of <BR>
          the origins of life be taught as theory rather than fact.<BR>
          (See Education Reporter, Dec. 1995.)<P>

          Republican legislators in California would like to<BR>
          penalize high schools for grade inflation as a form of<BR>
          consumer fraud. A 1993-94 study of freshmen at the 22<BR>
          campuses of the California State University system<BR>
          showed that nearly 50% of first-time freshmen need<BR>
          remedial courses in math, English, and writing. Many<BR>
          students graduate from high school with above B<BR>
          averages but still need remedial classes. Legislators<BR>
          proposed that high schools pay 100 percent of the cost<BR>
          of remedial work for students who receive a 3.8 or<BR>
          higher grade point average in college prep classes.<BR>
          Proponents of the legislation blame the remediation<BR>
          problem on the emphasis on self-esteem and the <BR>
          failure of bilingual education.<P>

          College freshmen are more conservative on certain<BR>
          issues than in years past. According to the Higher<BR>
          Education Research Institute, student support for<BR>
          legalized abortion and casual sex has dropped over the<BR>
          past 7-10 years. An all-time high attended a religious<BR>
          service during the past year.<P>

                                 
EAGLE FORUM<BR>
- ----------------------------------------------<BR>
Be sure to get on our Eagle Forum Alert List!!<BR>
Tell a friend about us!<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.basenet.net/~eagle">http://www.basenet.net/~eagle</A><P>
</A>

<A NAME="eagle"><HR>
From: Eagle Forum (eagle@accessus.net)<BR>
Date: Sun, 28 Apr 1996 20:30:42 -0500<BR>
Subject: C-NEWS: Capitol Hill Eagle Alert 4/27/96<P>

Capitol Hill Eagle Alert<P>

              Eagle Forum Legislative Office, Washington, DC<BR>
                           Phone: (202) 544-0353<P>

                                                         April 27, 1996<P>

                       ARE YOU OPPOSED TO CAREERS???<P>

                          THE TIME TO ACT IS NOW!!<P>

CAREERS, H.R. 1617, and its Senate counterpart, S. 143, the Workforce
Development Act, are still in conference and the conferees are hurrying to
finish the final bill (conference report) as quickly as they can. The House
Leadership plans to bring the conference report to the floor for final
passage as soon as it is ready. This means it can come up at any time! The
situation is critical!!! Many Members think there is little grassroots
opposition to the legislation, and that the opposition is being driven by a
few Washington, DC conservative leaders.<P>

The final version of the bill is not available, but because both the House
and Senate approve of and agree on the provisions we find most
objectionable (the "national data base" called the Labor Market Information
System, and the Workforce Development Boards), it is unlikely that the
conference report will be one we can accept. If this is ONLY a consolidation
bill, why are these provisions NECESSARY?<P>

If the CAREERS bill is to be stopped, the time to act is now. The House
Leadership must hear from real" voters today. The message is simple: NO
CAREERS THIS YEAR!!<P>

                        ---------------------------<P>

ACTION: Call and fax the following Members of the House the message:<P>

NO CAREERS THIS YEAR!<P>

Let them know that the conservative, grassroots voters are adamantly
opposed to this bill, and do not want it passed into law. Please contact
five friends who will also make the calls. Make the same calls again
tomorrow!<P>

These Members need to get hundreds of calls IMMEDIATELY!!<P>

1.) Speaker Newt Gingrich: phone - 202-225-0600; fax - 202-225-7733
     (Dan Meyer, Chief of Staff).<P>

     Message: Conservative voters do not want this bill to become law.        
     This bill is wholly inconsistent with the "Republican Revolution" 
     and we need Speaker Gingrich to stand with the grassroots in 
     opposition to the bill. NO CAREERS THIS YEAR!<P>

2.) Majority Leader Dick Armey: phone - 202-225-4000; fax- 202-226-8100
     (Mr. Kerry Knott, Chief of Staff) At a speech at the Heritage
     Foundation last month, Rep. Armey pushed CAREERRS as one of the 
     good things this Congress will do in the next several months. Mr.
     Armey is responsible for scheduling bills to be voted on, and he
     has tentatively scheduled this one for the first week in May.<P>

     Message: DO NOT LET THIS CONFERENCE REPORT COME TO THE FLOOR. The 
     bill is opposed by the conservative base and has been applauded by
     Bill Clinton. Let the bill remain in conference, and die in
     conference. NO CAREERS THIS YEAR!<P>

3.) Budget Chairman John Kasich: phone-202-225-5355; fax-202-226-5483.
     According to reliable sources, Mr. Kasich has been one of the most
     vocal supporters of CAREERS behind the scenes. He has been urging
     other Members of the leadership to pass this bill. Apparently, he
     is attracted to the (small) savings that come from "consolidating" 
     the various job training programs. He needs to hear that CAREERS is 
     bad policy, and Congress must reject bad policy no matter how much 
     savings are involved.<P>

     Message: Stop pushing CAREERS!! We do not want CAREERS THIS YEAR!<P>

           These Members must hear TODAY from real, live voters!<P>

      CAPITOL SWITCHBOARD: (202) 224-3121-Senate; (202) 225-3121-House<P>
- ---------------------------------------------------<P>

            Send E-mail to Eagle Forum at: eagle@accessus.net<P>

     (If you send mail to eagle@basenet.net -- we will still receive it.)<P>

</A>

<A NAME="ultimate"><HR>
From: Steve Ertelt (ertelt@netcentral.net)<BR>
Date: Sun, 28 Apr 1996 13:55:48 -0500 (CDT)<BR>
Subject: C-NEWS: Ultimate celebrates one-year anniversary<P>

INTERNET INFORMATION RELEASE<P>

April 28, 1996                             Ultimate Pro-Life Resource List<BR>
Contact:  ertelt@netcentral.net                 Your one-stop info source.<BR>
Redistribution permitted.                  <A HREF="http://www.prolife.org/ultimate">http://www.prolife.org/ultimate</A><P>

                ---------------------------------------------<P>

Ultimate celebrates one-year anniversary<P>

        With the end of April, the Internet's one-stop source for right to
life information celebrates its first highly successful year.<P>

        Since its inception in April 1995, the Ultimate Pro-Life Resource
List has assisted thousands in finding up-to-date information and has
quickly become the most comprehensive listing of right to life resources
on the internet. It offers information including educational factsheets,
adoption resources, abortion alternatives, opinion pieces, timely news
items, the Ultimate Political Corner, and much more.<P>

        By virtue of its high-quality presentation and plethora oof
resources, Ultimate has received several net-related awards. Calling it
"remarkable for its depth and diversity," Point Communications named it as
one of the top five percent of all internet sites. It also highlighted
Ultimate's lack of "virulence" and sensationalism. Other awards include
mention of Ultimate in the Internet Clearinghouse and awards as the
Political Site of the Day and the Conservative Site of the Day. Ultimate
received a featured billing in Town Hall and has been listed on scores of
political and other internet sites.<P>

        Thanks to those who have stopped by Ultimate and who have written
to me to offer their comments about it. We will continue to offer the
highest quality right to life information in a positive and user-friendly
manner.<P>

The Ultimate Pro-Life Resource List<BR>
<A HREF="http://www.prolife.org/ultimate">http://www.prolife.org/ultimate</A><P>

Steven A. Ertelt<BR>
ertelt@netcentral.net<P>
</A>

