<A NAME="congress"><HR>
From: Joe Velasquez <joe@velasquez.com><BR>
Date: Sun, 28 Apr 1996 12:44:20 -0700<BR>
Subject: C-NEWS: Congress Action 04/28/96<P>

<CENTER>                         CONGRESS ACTION                April 28 1996<BR>
                         ===============<BR>
              Kim Weissman 74157.1507@compuserve.com</CENTER><P>

STUPID IS AS STUPID DOES: Has the republican party decided it does 
not like leadership, or has it simply decided that, as worn out and 
useless as liberal ideas are, they are preferable to the hard work 
necessary to restore our nation to some semblance of the 
Constitutional republic it once was?<P>

   Unable to muster the courage needed to control wasteful and 
unconstitutional spending by stopping wasteful and unconstitutional 
spending, the republican majority, with the happy concurrence of 
many democrats, passed a Line Item Veto, and effectively passed the 
legislative buck to the Executive, giving the president even more 
power to blackmail congress and perhaps even increase pork spending. 
("Give me my billion for midnight basketball or I'll line out that 
road project in your district.") If Congress is unable to legislate 
the hard decisions they were sent to Washington to make, they should 
all just pack up and go home, and stop inflicting their arrogance on 
the rest of us who pay their salaries. They might as well do so 
anyway, having declared themselves superfluous with the Line Item 
Veto.<P>

   Then there is the Balanced Budget Amendment. Spending other 
people's money (ours) with profligate abandon, and like a drunk 
unable to resist just one more for the road, the beltway geniuses 
have hit upon the perfect solution: pass a Constitutional Amendment 
which will result in the federal courts deciding what they can and 
cannot spend money on. After all, the courts don't have enough 
autocratic power as it is, so give them some more. Then the 
president can pack his bags along with congress and they can all go 
home, and let the country be run by nine lifetime tenured potentates.<P>

    Next in the grab-bag of the absurd is Term Limits. They tell us, 
"Since we cannot be trusted to retire when we have outlived our 
usefulness, and since you voters are too stupid and complaisant to 
throw us out when we need throwing out, we'll just put the 
government on automatic pilot and let the law throw us all out, 
good, bad, and indifferent." And we voters, living down to the low 
opinion our legislators have of us, clamor, "Yes, please stop us 
before we vote again." Why? Because We, the People are incompetent 
to exercise our votes intelligently, for the greater good of the 
nation rather than for our own narrow self interest. This is the 
opinion our ruling elites have of us, and in our demand for Term 
Limits prove they are correct.<P>

   And what about the glowing promise of the conservative 
revolution, the promise to shrink the bloated federal government, to 
return self government to the States and the people? Which major 
program or agency has actually been eliminated? Which 
unconstitutional exercise of federal power has been curbed? Which 
oppressive federal regulations have been cut? What tax reform has 
been enacted, which taxes have been cut? What authority has been 
returned to parents to raise and to educate their children? On the 
plus side, a little noticed bill passed which mandates Congressional 
review of all regulations and allows affected businesses to take 
federal agencies to court. On the downside, a GOP response to the 
democrat minimum wage push, which would get the IRS even more deeply 
involved in wage decisions through EITC reform, and result in two 
equally qualified employees working side by side doing the same job 
getting different wages, because one has 1 child and the other has 2.<P>

   Far from seeing government shrink, we have seen an actual 
expansion: censoring the Internet and television content, violating 
our privacy and impairing our Constitutional rights in the guise of 
fighting terrorism, and policy surrenders ranging from AmeriCorps to 
funding for overseas abortion programs. The only real deficit 
reduction has come from the temporarily reduced funding while the 
government operated under the continuing resolutions of last winter. 
But no structural changes in big-cost entitlement programs.<P>

   Compare today's citizens with the character of the citizens of 
those 13 colonies who decided they were entitled to the right to 
control their own lives, and no longer wanted to cede that control 
to some distant bureaucrats. Imagine their courage and personal 
integrity as they pledged, and often sacrificed, everything they 
held dear to throw off the burdens of an oppressive government and 
"...to provide new Guards for their future Security", a new 
government deriving its just powers from the "Consent of the 
Governed." Unlike the beltway anointed who upbraid us for not 
putting our faith in government, the Founders viewed government with 
profound suspicion, and reserved their faith for other objects.<P>

   Now imagine the reaction of the Founders if they returned 209 
years later to survey the results of their handiwork of 1787, and 
they are told they would pay half of every dollar they earned to, 
for, or as a result of mandates from government; that they would see 
their land stolen and their livelihoods destroyed by the dictate of 
a government bureaucrat; that they would no longer have the right to 
control the education of their own children; that they would not be 
permitted to defend themselves and their loved ones from criminal 
predators intentionally loosed in their midst by their own 
government; that they would be vilified if they tried to bring 
religious piety to their public duties; that if they desired to 
start a business they would first have to seek permission from some 
bureaucrat who would, if permission were granted, tell them who they 
could hire and how much they had to pay; that their personal 
communications would be subject to oversight by faceless bureaucrats 
who could put them in prison if they said things deemed 
unacceptable; that the government created by the Constitution they 
adopted would daily, arrogantly, and with impunity ignore the limits 
placed on it by the very document which gave it legitimacy. Is this 
truly the country they created, or would they think their beloved 
America had been taken over by some foreign tyrant? How would they 
reconcile the fact that we in this country still pay lip service to 
that same Constitution, yet live as we do under a government as 
hostile to the liberties they thought they had safeguarded as any 
eighteenth century monarchy?<P>

   What would that Founding generation think of their heirs living 
thus? Would they deem us to be a stupid people? Maybe, seeing the 
billions we spend on pre-natal care, yet wantonly killing our unborn 
by the millions, often by methods which the Spanish Inquisition 
would consider barbaric; seeing the loony left adopt the Unabomber 
as their hero and the loony right adopt the Freemen as theirs; 
seeing how we have squandered the heritage of Freedom they fought and 
suffered and died for. The Founders warned of the dangers of a 
government which defined the limits of its own power, for the powers 
of such a government have no limits. They adopted a written 
Constitution for the express purpose of imposing external limits on 
the new government they created, limits which were not to be defined 
by that government itself but by the People from whom those powers 
were derived. Our federal government has arrogated to itself the 
sole authority to define, through one of its own subdivisions -- the 
Supreme Court -- the limits of its own powers. Is it any wonder that 
our federal government has rarely found its own exercise of power to 
be improper?<P>

   "A constitution is a thing antecedent to a government, and a 
government is only the creature of a constitution. The constitution 
of a country is not the act of its government, but of the people 
constituting a government. It is the body of elements, to which you 
can refer, and quote article by article; and which contain the 
principles on which the government shall be established, the manner 
in which it shall be organized, the powers it shall have...and the 
principles on which it shall act and by which it shall be bound. A 
government on the principles on which constitutional governments, 
arising out of society are established, cannot have the right of 
altering itself. If it had, it would be arbitrary. It might make 
itself what it pleased; and wherever such a right is set up, it 
shows that there is no constitution." -- Thomas Paine (The Rights of 
Man, 1791)<P>

WHERE CREDIT IS DUE: In the 1960's liberals conceived a variety of 
social programs designed to eliminate poverty, crime, drug use, 
illegitimacy, and broken families. That every one of those problems 
is worse now, by any measure, than when liberals set out to fix them 
is beyond dispute. The architects of that massive social engineering 
claim that unforseen factors and outside events caused the failure 
of their vision, and deny that it was their vision itself which was 
misconceived, counterproductive, and wrong-headed from the start.<P>

   Imagine for a moment that we looked around today and saw that 
poverty, crime, drug use, illegitimacy, and broken families had all 
been eliminated. Can anyone deny that the liberal social architects 
would claim full credit for their successes, and deservedly so? 
However, when we survey our society today we do not see successes, 
we see instead abject, monumental failures. Liberal social 
architects, and their liberal democrat allies in the Congress, a 
Congress which they controlled over that entire period of time and 
which enacted all the laws and created all the programs demanded by 
the social architects, bear full responsibility for the dismal state 
of our society. Good or bad, we must give credit where credit is 
due: the social decay we see all around us is their doing, and 
theirs alone.<P>

END<P>

Congress Action is available on its own web page at <P>

<A HREF="http://www.aimnet.com/~jbv/congress_action.html">http://www.aimnet.com/~jbv/congress_action.html</A> <P>

and on FTP site at <P>

<A HREF="ftp://ftp.aimnet.com/pub/users/jbv/congress_action/">ftp.aimnet.com</A><P>

/pub/users/jbv/congress_action/<P>

</A>

<A NAME="internet"><HR>
From: sallen@iguild.org (Steven J. Allen)<BR>
