<html>
<body>
<title>Mark Genrich -- The Lights Went Out... Again</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
The Lights Went Out... Again
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<br> By Mark Genrich
<br> Deputy Editorial Page Editor
<br> The Phoenix Gazette
</i>
<p>
President Clinton's memo to Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary demanded an
explanation for the power outage on July 2.
<p>
He noted that the outage in the Western power grid disrupted electric service
to hundreds of thousands of customers in 15 Western states and had a "ripple
effect" as power stations across the vast grid automatically shut down as the
result of experiencing a surge.
<p>
The president said that the "outages caused numerous problems throughout the
region, including disruptions of train service, traffic problems, loss of
air-conditioning, interruption of telephone service and interference with
water supplies," and he directed Secretary O'Leary to provide him with a
report that analyzed the cause of the outage, described the extent and
duration of the outage and analyzed whether the outage could have been
prevented.
<p>
The president wanted to know whether the Western Systems Coordinating Council
(WSCC) electric reliability system responded as anticipated to the initial
outage.
<p>
The council was formed in 1967 by 40 electric-power systems in a region
encompassing nearly 1.8 million square miles. The WSCC is the largest of nine
regional councils of the North American Electric Reliability Council (NERC).
<p>
NERC formed in the aftermath of the Nov. 9, 1965, blackout that affected the
Northeast and Ontario, Canada with a mission "to promote the reliability of
the electricity supply for North America."
<p>
A not-for-profit corporation controlled by the nine regional councils, NERC
includes investor-owned, municipal/state/provincial, cooperative and federal
electric utilities in the United States, Canada, and a small part of Mexico,
plus all major independent power producers and electric-power marketers. 
<p>
Its basic mission is to keep the lights on, which is why President Clinton
reasonably inquired as to the adequacy of North American electric-reliability
systems and recommendations for any operational or regulatory changes.
<p>
"I have directed that these steps be taken to assure the reliability of the
nation's electricity infrastructure," said the president, adding, "A steady
supply of power is a vital factor in both the local and national economies
and is essential for the safety of all Americans. The swift implementation of
this directive will assure that these interests will be protected."
<p>
On Aug. 2, Secretary O'Leary answered the president, conceding that the July
2 incident was "preventable."
<p>
She went on to say that "in concert with industry, we are taking action to
strengthen the nation's electric reliability systems." 
<p>
Here is her official explanation for the July outage:
<p>
<blockquote>
"A transmission line sagged too close to a tree, creating a short circuit and
causing the line to disconnect automatically. A protective device on a
parallel line misinterpreted the short circuit and disconnected its line."
</blockquote>
<p>
Loss of the two lines triggered a procedure to shut down two generating units
at a nearby power plant served by the two lines because the generators'
output otherwise would overload remaining transmission lines.
<p>
Mrs. O'Leary explained to the president that bulk electric systems in the
West are designed and operated to be able to absorb the stresses of such a
combination of events without further cascading of the local outage.
<p>
But in the July incident "the initial event propagated a sequence of events
rippling across the entire Western power grid, interrupting service to over 2
million customers in 14 states. While the service was restored to customers
within periods ranging from a few minutes to over six hours, the scope and
speed of the outage were disturbing in their implications."
<p>
In a July 31 report to address the reliability of electricity supply and
delivery systems in North America, NERC said the system "as existing and
planned, will be adequate to meet customer electricity demands in the near
term and are capable of being operated reliably under a wide range of system
conditions. Unanticipated equipment problems and extreme weather in any
region can combine to strain the bulk electric systems even when projections
and assessments show these systems to be adequate."
<p>
There were two specific areas of reliability concern, including limited
operable generating capacity in New England and delays in the completion of
the proposed line between West Virginia and Virginia.
<p>
But, NERC said, "The transition to more competitive wholesale electricity
markets has significant implications to the continued reliable operation of
bulk electric systems in North America, which NERC is addressing. In the long
term, the adequacy of generating capacity and transmission systems is less
certain because the industry is moving to a more fully competitive
electricity supply market."
<p>
Meanwhile, the WSCC's report identified specific equipment failures and
operational deficiencies that contributed to the July outage, "which already
have been corrected. These corrective actions have substantially reduced the
possibility that a similar sequence of events could occur in the region."
<p>
Then the lights went out . . . again.
<p>
The August 10 incident struck homes and businesses from Oregon to Mexico.
<p>
"Actually, this may be a blessing because it's a wake-up call to say that
reliability is not a mere detail - it's critical," says Renz Jennings,
chairman of the Arizona Corporation Commission.
<p>
Commissioner Jennings is absolutely correct.
<p>
Reliability is critical, especially as the country prepares for competition
among providers of power. 
<p>
So, the question could reasonably be asked, despite all these reports and
assurances and pronouncements about reliability, why do the lights keep going
out?
<p>
Arizona is home to the largest nuclear power plant in the nation. Yet this
massive electrical generating station was knocked off line . . . by a tree .
. . in Oregon? 
<p>
What is wrong with this picture?
<p>
Regulators are correct to be concerned about the reliability of power, but
they cannot escape their own measure of responsibility for ensuring that
reliability.
<p>
If the grid in which a regulator's state participates is insufficient to
allow for disturbances in other parts of the region, that should be a clue
that something is amiss with regulatory oversight.
<p>
Did the nation's regulators sit by while utilities downsized and
re-engineered to a point beyond where customers could be assured dependable
service?
<p>
Was it a tree in Oregon that was responsible for the August outage or was it
rank utility greed? That is, were utilities pumping power along lines of the
Western grid, knowing full well that they were pushing the limits of its
capacity, for the sake of additional profits?
<p>
And, what responsibility does the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission bear?
It has stewardship over wholesale electric rates and service standards, as
well as the transmission of electricity in interstate commerce. Has it given
the green light to competition without first ensuring the integrity of the
transmission system?
<p>
A power outage - two power outages - of proportions great enough to capture
the concern of the president suggest U.S. utility regulators need to be far
more attentive to the infrastructures in their states and what future demand
will mean to an already overloaded system.
<p>
Oversight, after all, whether it is in Arizona or Washington, should be
focused on reliability of service for the people who pay the bills - the same
people who are wondering how long the lights will stay on this time.
<p>
<p>
<center>
# # #
<br>
<p>

<a href="mailto:MLGedit@aol.com">Mark Genrich</a> is Deputy Editorial Page Editor of <i>The Phoenix Gazette</i>.<br> He can be reached at 
602-271-8472.
<p>
(Copyright, Phoenix Newspapers Inc.)
</center>
<p>
