<body>
<title>David F. Nolan -- Stop The Browne-Out!</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
UNCONVENTIONAL WISDOM
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<i>
<b>Stop The Browne-Out!</b>   
<br> by David F. Nolan
</i>
<p>
     Numerous polls have shown that a large majority of U.S. voters would like to see a credible third party as an alternative to the Republicans and Democrats. The choices offered by the Big Two often seem like a choice between spinach and broccoli, especially to anyone who sincerely desires a major reduction in the size, cost and intrusiveness of government at all levels.
     <p>The current presidential election is a case in point. Bob Dole has been aptly described as "the tax collector for the welfare state," and his new-found devotion to tax cuts seems forced and hollow.  Every poll shows Clinton beating Dole by 13 to 22 percentage points, with an equivalent edge in the Electoral College. Consequently, nobody seems very excited about the Clinton-Dole contest or a series of debates between the two men.
	 <p>Yet the supposedly "non-partisan" Commission on Presidential Debates seems determined to exclude all other candidates from any debates that may take place. They argue that once they start admitting third-party contenders, there's no place to draw the line. Janet Brown, Executive Director of  the Commission, recently stated that there are "150 candidates" for President, and that if anyone beyond Clinton and Dole were invited to participate, the result would be chaos.
	 <p>This contention, to put it politely, is a bunch of hooey.
<p>In fact, there are only four or five third-party presidential
candidates on enough states' ballots to win a mathematical majority of the Electoral College, and only two -- Ross Perot and Harry Browne -- who will be on all 50 ballots. Three others -- Howard Phillips, Ralph Nader and John Hagelin -- will be on the ballot in more than half the states. That's it.
	<p> Of these five, only Perot and Browne represent serious alternatives: Perot because of his money, and Browne because he's the standard bearer for the Libertarian Party, generally acknowledged to be America's only real third party. The Libertarians already have close to 200 elected office-holders, nearly 1,000 candidates, and 50-state ballot status. The non-partisan Congressional Quarterly has described the LP as "the most significant third party in decades".
	<p> And yet, the Commission on Presidential Debates seems determined to ignore Browne, even as they grudgingly discuss Perot's participation. Their reasons are purely political; the Dole campaign wants Browne kept out because they're afraid that he'll take votes away from Dole, and thus aid Clinton. Indeed, Dole operatives have floated the suggestion that lefty Ralph Nader ought to be considered for inclusion, in the hope that he will draw votes away from Clinton!
	<p>News Flash from the Future: Dole's gonna lose anyway, guys! Big-time. And in the long run, the cause of cutting back big government will be served far better by including Browne and bringing his message to the electorate than it will by reducing Dole's drubbing.
	<p> This point is not lost on many in the media. As of September 5th, some 23 newspapers have carried columns or editorials calling for Harry Browne's inclusion. Those writing in favor range from Joseph Sobran (conservative) to David Broder (liberal); the newspapers advocating Browne's participation include the Denver Post, Cleveland Plain Dealer and Orange County Register. The Register's editorial summed things up nicely, saying that Browne's inclusion would "blow some fresh air through the stale smog of statism that passes for political discourse between the major parties."
     <p>Additionally, some 177 talk radio hosts, including Michael Reagan, Gene Burns and Bob Grant have already spoken out in favor of Harry Browne's inclusion. Of these, one-third say they plan to vote for Browne themselves, while two-thirds simply feel that his inclusion would lend substance to the debates.
     <p>Ultimately, however, Harry Browne will be included in the debates only if there is massive public demand for his inclusion. You can help, if you are so inclined, by writing to 
the Commission on Presidential Debates at 601 Thirteenth Street, NW, Suite 310S, Washington, DC 20005 and urging them to include Harry. Or, you can e-mail them at <a href="mailto:debates96@usa.pipeline.com">debates96@usa.pipeline.com</a>. But time is of the essence; the decisions regarding the debates will be made by no later than September 15th. The time to act is now!	
  <p>
DFN
<p>
<center>
--------------------------------------------------------------
</center>
<br>
<i>
UNCONVENTIONAL WISDOM is a column of commentary and opinion by David 
F. Nolan, a self-described "radical Constitutionalist" who first 
became politically active during the Goldwater campaign. In the 
intervening years, Mr. Nolan has worked with the Young Americans for 
Freedom, the Liberty Amendment Committee, the Libertarian Party and 
the International Society for Individual Liberty. He presently makes 
his home in Orange County, California. He may be reached by <a href="mailto:73303.1612@CompuServe.com">e-mail</a>.
</i>
<p><p>

