<html>
<body>
<title>Acton Institute -- Don't Even Mention It</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Don't Even Mention It
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

<i>by John-Peter Pham</i>
<p>
America’s political conventions take on the air of a religious tent 
meeting worthy of the Great Awakening. Speakers take to the podium to 
solemnly catechize the faithful and admonish the unbeliever about the 
"real issues" at stake. Yet voters have a history of turning on 
candidates who dare speak truly unpleasant truths. Like many a modern 
Milquetoast preacher, the major parties tend to agree to remain silent 
about certain hard issues.
<p>
The following is my list of ten such issues, five domestic and five 
foreign. While not all admit political solutions, they are questions 
of major national and international concern. They deserve a reasonable 
consideration in the public discourse.
<p>
<b>1. Divorce.</b> Both presidential candidates will pay homage to 
"family values"; Republicans denouncing abortion and Democrats 
skewering deadbeat dads. But what about divorce itself, the primary 
assault on the family? Tragically, over 600,000 families with minor 
children break up each year. The children of divorced parents are more 
likely to suffer from physical and emotional problems than children of 
married parents.
<p>
<b>2. Teen sex.</b> Both parties decry increased births to unwed 
mothers. However, no one will even raise the far more fundamental 
issue: teen pregnancies don't happen without teen sex. Nearly thirty 
years of progressive sex education in schools has done worse than 
nothing. Teen sexual activity has increased several-fold. Solutions 
require frank discussion.
<p>
<b>3. New Tactics in the war on Drugs.</b> Both parties call for 
better enforcement of drug laws and increased funding. But isn't it 
time to admit that there is more to the problem? Billions have already 
been spent, prisons are overflowing, yet more lethal drugs are 
available than ever before. Legalization may not be the solution, but 
it deserves to be at least calmly and rationally discussed.
<p>
<b>4. Fundamental legal reform.</b> What is wrong with a judicial 
system that awards millions to a woman who spills hot coffee on 
herself? A system that releases legions of guilty offenders because 
fleeing from the police does not constitute "suspicious behavior"? The 
trial lawyers have contributed millions in cash and in kind, meanwhile 
serious reforms of the judicial system is not being discussed.
<p>
<b>5. Government and individual responsibilities.</b> The national 
consensus is that there should be less government interference with 
the lives and businesses of citizens. But what about the necessary 
corollary of individual responsibility? Farmers plant on flood plains 
and expect government grants when flood waters rise. Smokers light up 
packs a day and then lobby for assistance when they come down with 
cancer. No national renewal is possible until there is a national 
consensus that we are responsible for our own actions.
<p>
<b>6. Nuclear and conventional arms proliferation.</b> Nuclear weapons 
(and know-how) are spreading after the breakup or the Soviet Union to 
a frightful coterie of pariah states, including the likes of Iran and 
Libya. Sophisticated conventional weapons are traded with the tacit 
encouragement of governments who think only of keeping weapons 
manufacturers in business. Pray it won’t take a catastrophe to awaken 
us to this danger.
<p>
<b>7. China.</b> In 1992, Bill Clinton attacked President Bush for 
being "soft" on communist China. As president, however, he was no 
different from his predecessor. And Bob Dole? He has remained 
conspicuously silent. China is a potential multi-billion dollar market 
for U.S. products and cheap labor -- some of it, as Harry Wu 
demonstrated at great personal risk, is prison labor. China has the 
worst human rights record in the world. But politicians won’t upset 
the apple cart of the multinational business lobby.
<p>
<b>8. Vietnam.</b> A year ago, the U.S. restored diplomatic relations 
with communist Vietnam amid much fanfare. The balance sheet? No trade 
agreement, no great new markets. Instead, the old dinosaurs were 
returned for another five-year term by the recent congress of the 
Vietnamese Communist party, which continues to repress any political 
dissent and to prosecute religious groups. Vietnam is still too 
emotional or an issue to be bantered about in any American electoral 
season.
<p>
<b>9. Foreign Aid.</b> Video clips of starving children and flooded 
villages tug at our heartstrings. However, compassion for victims must 
necessarily include a concern for their future. The public forum has 
yet to seriously engage the debate which is now at least a decade old 
among scholars: in the long run, does foreign aid help or hinder its 
beneficiaries?
<p>
<b>10. Realpolitik.</b> American policy makers tend to reflect the 
general public's desire for a kinder, gentler world. Potential 
international conflicts are ignored in a wish to have no enemies. 
Shouldn't there be a rational analysis of our strategic interests in 
NATO and Pacific Rim security, especially with their new and shifting 
alliances? In the long run, ignoring the march of history in favor of 
an idyllic pipe-dream may be the ultimate tragedy of this year of: 
"don’t even mention it."
<p>
<center>

         # # # # #
<p>
<br>
Father John-Peter Pham, a priest of the Catholic Diocese of Peoria, is 
a Fellow of the Action Institute for the Study of Religion and Liberty 
in Grand Rapids, MI.
</center>
<p>
<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
