<html>
<body>
<title>Lari McDonald -- Let's Think About It</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>Let's Think About It
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

<i>by Lari McDonald</i>
<p>


Let's think about how some of the major social problems our state and 
nation faces have come about. I'm a conservative, activist citizen. 
I'm a Christian. I'm a registered Republican. Foundationally 
conservative citizens are usually Republicans. I believe we need to 
conserve the strong nation and society into which my generation was 
born and raised. I'm not an Ozzie and Harriet fan, but families were 
stable then. Education in public schools produced literate graduates 
prepared for productive lives in the workplace. And, they could read, 
write and cipher' Children weren't encouraged to be sexually active; 
few were parents in their early teens. A student would not kill a fellow 
student to get a fancy jacket or a pair of sneakers. Folks did not 
assume that neighbors should be forced through taxes to pay for 
government programs providing their "free" food, clothing, shelter 
and health care.
<p>
Liberal academic elitists and elected officials have conditioned you 
and me, our families, our schools, our communities, our nation to 
accept these kinds of social problems as a norm of some sort, with 
more taxes and programs to cure the ills. Conservatives say "no way"; 
these are all symptoms of a very sick society and the illness must be 
faced and treated. Liberal academic elitists and elected officials are 
selling America's future to the United Nations' world government where 
our lives would be supervised by agencies and laws totally apart from 
the American Constitution and its protection of our freedoms. Bit by 
bit, liberals have phased out the strengths and integrity of the 
United States with their do-good programs and massive taxes against 
our pocketbooks to pay for it all.
<p>
Who are these liberals? To be sure, there have always been liberals in 
the Republican party establishments on the state and national levels. 
Mostly, however, the ideas and laws out of which our social and 
political chaos have grown since the 1930s, with a real jump start in 
the 60s Great Society, were passed by Congresses and state 
legislatures, and county commissions, controlled by liberal Democrats.
<p>
It's fascinating that in just the past few years roughly 250 elected 
Democrats across the nation have changed to the Republican party 
because the ideas and practices of the Democratic party have deserted 
virtually all of the principles in which they believe and on which our 
American nation is founded. So, if you feel that you should have more 
take home pay and lower taxes, that families must be encouraged and 
strengthened for the most adequate raising of children, that public 
education must be systematically changed for improvement and freed up 
from unionized control, that parents killing their unborn children is 
wrong, <b>YOU ARE A CONSERVATIVE</b>.
<p>
If you're a conservative and registered as a Democrat, understand that 
there is no place in the Democratic party's thinking for you, your 
ideas and your value system.
<p>
Aha, you say, but your grandfather would turn over in his grave if you 
switched parties and registered as a Republican. Perhaps. But, he 
would have turned over years ago if he knew how close to destruction 
the American system has been brought by liberal Democratic control of 
legislative bodies for far too long.
<p>
Historically the Republican Party was founded in 1854 with the primary 
purpose of eliminating slavery from the United States. The number of 
hard working, taxpaying, upward mobile African American citizens who 
have changed party because of disagreement with liberal Democratic 
positions on critical issues affecting their lives and freedom, is 
exciting, very encouraging, and critical to the restoration of the 
stabilizing effect of conservative values to this state and nation.
<p>
Thank you.
<p>
Lari McDonald<br>
 4444 Rehobeth Church Road<br>
 Greensboro, N.C., 27406<br>
<p>
<i>
(July 25, 1996, comments to Guilford County Board of County 
Commissioners composed of 7 Democrats, 4 Republicans
<p>
These County Commission meetings are televised on public access TV 
twice in the week following each meeting, giving the speaker a 
relatively wider audience than just the persons in attendance at the 
meeting.)
</i>
<p>
<p>
<br>

