<html>
<body>
<title>The Union Leader</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote>
<center>
<H3>Dear Mr. Dole:</H3>
Don't Wait, Introduce Your Tax Cut Now!
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<P>
<I>Richard Lessner<BR>
The Union Leader<BR></I>
<P>
<BR>
<DD>That 15 percent across-the-board tax cut you and Jack Kemp are booming across the country just isn't cutting it with the voters.
<P>
Most Americans believe they're overtaxed.  And in the last six years a half-dozen states under the leadership of Republican governors have aggressively reduced taxes with results typically described as "spectacular" and "miraculous." 
<P>
So why hasn't your tax cut caught fire with the voters? Because a majority, doubtless recalling Bill Clinton's broken promise of a middle-class tax cut, believe your proposal is "just a political ploy."
<P>
Unless you can overcome this voter skepticism, the centerpiece of your campaign, the chief wedge issue between yourself and Bill Clinton will continue to fizzle. Standing up and telling the voters, "Look, people, Bob Dole really, really means it!" won't get the job done.
<P>
So, how do you get the voters to believe your tax cut is real? Easy. Have Newt and Trent introduce it in Congress -- right now!
<P>
This would have two good effects: First, it would take your tax cut out of the realm of insubstantial campaign promise and make it concrete. Second, it would drive the Democrats and Bill Clinton straight up the wall and make it the key issue in the campaign. Introducing the cut now would give it instant credibility.
<P>
Clearly, your campaign needs to do something dramatic -- and do it soon -- to begin closing the gap. So far, the initiative has been all the President's, as almost daily he unveils another federal goody. As Fred Barnes put it the other day, Mr. Dole, it's time to panic!
<P>
Doubtless you're getting plenty of unsolicited advice these days, and there's little reason to believe you'll pay much attention to ours. But so far all the wisdom of your high-priced Washington consultants hasn't amounted to a hill of beans. Unless you can figure a way to turn this around and put Mr. Clinton on the defensive, you're going to lose and lose badly.
<P>
Well, that's how we see it.
<P>
<BR>
<BR>
--Richard Lessner
<P>
<p>
<br>
<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>
</blockquote></blockquote>
</body>
