<body>
<title>The Hearthstone Press: Two Fair Tax Changes</title>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<blockquote><blockquote>

<center>
<h3>
Two Fair Tax Changes
</h3>
</center>
<p>
<HR Size=3 Width=30%>
<p>

Bob Dole has consulted his economic gurus on his policy strategy for 
the presidential election, and by the time this editorial appears in 
print, he may have signed onto a slate of tax cuts, including a 
capital gains tax cut and making social security taxes deductible.  
Both of these changes steer toward making income taxes fairer, and 
that is the source of their political appeal.
<p>
Capital gains taxes are especially unfair because those gains are 
often a result of inflation, inflicted on us by the same federal 
government that has the audacity to tax those gains.  At the very 
least, capital gains taxes should be indexed, using the consumer price 
index as a surrogate for the inflation rate just as it is used in 
government COLA's or in the government's own budget baseline.  If 
cost-of-living adjustments are fair on the spending side of 
government, then similar adjustments are due the owners of assets that 
appreciate because the government spends more than it takes in. 
<p>
Capital gains taxes can also be especially unfair under a graduated 
income tax when they treat the gains one accumulates over a long 
period of time as if it were income produced in one year.  Consider 
this: if you sell your small business, the gain you reap might push 
you up into the dreaded rich-man's tax bracket, even though you may 
have spent most of your working years living modestly so your business 
could grow.  While advocates of high tax rates for "the rich" might 
claim that the Clinton tax increases of 1993 affected only upper-
income taxpayers, one has to remember that income tax laws now do not 
differentiate between capital gains and regular income, so there is a 
special, bitter surprise for anyone who tries to cash in on his life's 
work. 
<p>
Allowing social security taxes to be deductible is also fair.  First 
of all, employers get to deduct their half of the tax (remember, the 
real rate you pay for Social Security and Medicare is double the 
amount indicated on your paycheck!); why shouldn't individuals get the 
same opportunity?  Also, income taxes should only tax people on their 
NET income, and FICA taxes always come straight off the top, no 
questions asked.  Just as state and local taxes are deductible, so 
should FICA taxes be deductible.  What is the argument for not making 
them so, except to say that the government wants your money and not 
letting you deduct FICA taxes is just a way of the government getting 
more of it.  
<p>
As for how Bob Dole might "pay for" these tax changes, he should 
assert from the start that high capital gains rates make many people 
find ways to avoid paying them.  Lower rates would flush out capital 
that is currently tied up in "mature" investments and let that capital 
flow to new enterprises, where most of our economic growth comes from.  
Letting working Americans keep more of what they earn not only fuels 
economic growth but it also makes them less dependent on government 
handouts.  Bob Dole should know that it is Congess's lack of 
discipline on spending that causes deficits, not their failure to suck 
more blood from the neck of the economy. Dole should embrace these two 
tax changes for the good of his party and for the good of his 
campaign. 

<p>
<br>

<center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a>
</center>

</body>
</html>
