<html>
<head>
<title>Presidents Go, Judges Stay</title>     
</head>     
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">     
     
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>     
<center>
<h3>
Presidents Go, Judges Stay
</h3>
</center>
<P>
<hr size=3 width=30%>
<i> 
<br>Monday, November 4, 1996 editorials
<br>by Lee Anderson, Editor and Publisher, <a href="http://www.chatfreepress.com">Chattanooga Free Press</a>
</i>
<p>
     Four years, or maybe eight. That's how long the next president of the United States will stay in office.
<p>
Terms are limited. Presidential power is limited.
<p>
Not so with justices of the United States Supreme Court.
<p>
Those nine ladies and gentlemen are appointed to their posts by presidents. They are confirmed by the Senate. Then they have
terms of "life,' on good behavior. And while a "life' term rarely means that for a murderer, it may really mean "life' for a
Supreme Court justice, unless he or she chooses to leave.
<p>
And power? The power of a president after four or eight years may be little more than that of an over-the-hill movie, TV or
sports star--if that much.
<p>
But the power of a justice of the Supreme Court is tremendous. And it will go on for many more years than his or her lifetime.
It may go on "forever' as a legal precedent.
<p>
Laws passed by Congress are often amended or repealed. But it's rare that a major ruling by the Supreme Court is reversed.
The court doesn't lightly make major change. And it takes two-thirds of the members of both houses of Congress and
ratification by three-fourths of the states to amend the Constitution legally to undo a judicial "amendment' of the Constitution
that five justices have decreed unconstitutionally.
<p>
Whoever is elected president on Tuesday may have the responsibility to name two, three or maybe even four Supreme Court
justices in the next four years!
<p>
Do you think you would like to have our country live virtually forever under the kind of rulings that appointees of Bill Clinton
would make?
<p>
If the Supreme Court and its justices operated as they should --as dispassionate referees of the law as it is written _ it wouldn't
matter who named the members of the court. All we would want would be intelligence, knowledge of the law and willingness
to work fairly. But that's not the way the high court does business.
<p>
The current Supreme Court is divided among three general segments, with occasional "migration' of some justices one way or
the other. One segment is conservative, tending to stick to the Constitution and law, ruling in protection of individual rights.
Another is liberal, tending to write what it "wishes' the law said to effect social change, increasing government intervention,
promoting "group' rights rather than individual freedom. The third group swings one way or the other, depending upon the case
and circumstances.
<p>
If Mr. Clinton is elected Tuesday, he is not going to appoint justices he knows will swing the court to the conservative side on
the Constitution and individualism.
<p>
If Sen. Dole is elected Tuesday, he is not knowingly going to name justices who will "make up their own law.'
<p>
In four years if Mr. Clinton wins or in four or eight years if Sen. Dole wins, both of them will be out of government. But two,
three or four Supreme Court justices--or even more--that one of them has appointed will still be there. And their rulings will
live long after them.
<p>
Think about that. We are electing more than a president on Tuesday.
<p>
We are indirectly "electing' some powerful Supreme Court justices.
     
</blockquote></blockquote>      

<P> <br><center>     
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">     
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">     
</a></center>     
<P>     
</body>     
