<DOCNO>WT16-B03-169</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA022-000237-B016-516</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.sbsc.org:80/abic/wethepeople.html.cgi 204.71.237.86 19970108033716 text/html 10246
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 03:37:30 GMT
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABICF - "Setting Limits: We the People"</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Bac
k in Charge" ISMAP></a><p>
<P>
<P>
<br>
<blockquote>
<CENTER><H2>We the People</H2>
<STRONG><EM>We the people of the United States of America...</EM></STRONG></CENTER>
<P><BR>
Somewhere between the First Federal Congress of 1787 and the 104th Congress, this defining opening statement to the Constitution of the United States of America lost its meaning.  What was once a "government of the people, by the people and for the people" has become a mockery of what the Founding Fathers envisioned. The citizen congress has become a welfare state for career politicians. The limited government has become a limitless government. And powers once reserved for the people have been lost in the politics of self-preservation.
<P>
There is little doubt that the "government of the people" envisioned by the Founding Fathers was one of limited federal powers. The framers of the Constitution certainly never imagined a "government by the people" run by career politicians so entrenched in their position of power as to be almost entirely removed from their constituency. And their ideal of a "government for the people" surely could not have been one that passes on the burden of a huge national debt from one generation to the next.
<P>	
The historical principle of a limited central government cannot be ignored by any serious student of the origins of our Constitution. James Madison wrote that "[i]n framing a government which is to be administered by men over men, the great difficulty lies in this: You must first enable the government to control itself." Thomas Jefferson professed: "I own that I am not a friend of a very energetic government. It is always oppressive."
<P>	
What a distance we have traveled since 1787. The seemingly endless involvement of the federal government in every facet of our lives has far exceeded the worst fears of even the most vocal anti-federalist in the late 18th century.
<P>
As we prepare to move into the next century - and the next millennium - it is time for "we the people" to reclaim the vision of the Founding Fathers. We can only do this by restating in the Constitution the principles of limits that were implicit in the Founders' view of the nation. And only then will we put Americans back in charge of the government of the people. 
<P>
<H3><CENTER>LIMITED TIME + LIMITED MONEY<BR>
= LIMITED GOVERNMENT</CENTER>
</H3>
Central to the concept of a limited government was the principal of limited national service, evidenced most clearly by the example of Washington, Jefferson and every President until Roosevelt, but also evidenced by the short tenure of Members of Congress in the 18th and 19th centuries. The idea of a representative government is that the people select one of their own, a member of their community, and dispatch that person to the seat of government for a short time to represent the views and perspectives of their community before he or she returns home to once again live and work in that community. If allowed to linger for a protracted period of time, the representative becomes the federal government's emissary to the people, instead of the other way around. The dynamic of representation has been reversed and become the opposite of what was intended.
<P>
Imposing limited tenure on Members of Congress restores the principal of representative democracy to its proper function. People who make laws for others should do so knowing with certainty that they will soon return to private life and live and work under those laws. This is the ultimate check on the powers of the legislature. This is what democratic self-rule was supposed to be about.
<P>
Term limits are an essential part of restricting the role of the federal government. If we can limit the time that politicians spend in Washington, we can fundamentally change the role of the federal government in our lives. If Members of Congress know coming in that there is a time certain that they must leave, it will change the mind set of the institution and of the Members themselves.
<P>
Term limits are the surest way to reform Congress, addressing the issues of campaign finance reform, lobbying reform, the seniority system and the perks and privileges of the ruling class that have become a plague on the institution.
<P>
Equally important to the concept of limited government is the principle of limited funds and fiscal responsibility. The Founding Fathers recognized this as they addressed economic issues throughout the Constitution. Never in their wildest dreams could they have imagined a national debt over $3.4 trillion.
<P>
Unfortunately, that principle has been lost on the Congress of today. Not having ended the year in a surplus for the past 25 years, they have habitually and routinely abandoned the concept of a balanced budget. They have shown themselves both unwilling and unable to spend within our means.
<P>
Federal spending is inextricably linked to tenure in Congress. Studies by the National Taxpayers Union demonstrate that junior Representatives have always been more fiscally conservative than senior Representatives. Stephen Moore wrote in 1994 that "if we truly want to get government spending under control, much more important than changing the party controlling Congress is reducing the length of congressional careers via term limits ... research indicates that the longer a member has been in Congress, the worse is his or her voting record (as to spending) - and that is true of members of both parties."
<P>
By writing the two axioms of limited time and limited money into the federal constitution, our national government and its leaders will, for the first time in decades, be subject to the external controls and boundaries envisioned by the Constitution in its original form.
<P>

<CENTER><H3>Term Limits and Balanced Budget Amendments:<BR>The Bookends of the Contract with America</H3></CENTER>

The constitutional amendments to limit congressional terms and balance the federal budget were (and still are) the "bookends" of the GOP Contract with America - enjoying massive public support and reflecting the ideal of a permanently restructured federal government. Much of the electoral success enjoyed by Republican candidates in 1994 can be attributed to these two wildly popular provisions.
<P>
These constitutional amendments continue to enjoy the overwhelming support of the American people. George Will wrote in 1992: "There are just two things that three-fourths of the American people want that Congress will not permit. One is a balanced budget amendment; the other is term limits for legislators. These are anathema to Congress because careerism is the shared creed of Democrans and Republicrats, and deficit spending - burdening future voters to buy today's voters - is the key to careerism... term limits would change the motives and behavior of legislators."
<P>
Since 1990, more than 25 million people have voted in favor of limiting the terms of their congressional delegations and twenty-three states have passed congressional term limits. In January, 1996, a nationwide survey of 1,000 registered voters conducted by The Tarrance Group found that 77 percent of the country's electorate favor term limits.
<P>
According to the survey, Republicans (80%), Democrats (71%) and Independents (81%) all favor limits on the number of terms federally elected officials can serve. The support is extremely widespread, never falling below 60% with any voter group. The term limits issue cuts across party lines, social strata and economic status, making it one of the most widely popular government reform measures ever proposed.
<P>
Support for the balanced budget amendment is equally strong. Several Gallup polls conducted at various times in 1995 consistently showed over 71 percent of the American people favoring the balanced budget amendment.
<P>
The American people instinctively know that term limits will permanently limit the time that politicians can spend in Washington and, further, that the balanced budget amendment will permanently limit the money that politicians in Washington can spend. Together, the two amendments will restore to the Constitution the notion of a finite federal government - something that was implicit in the design of our government and understood by the Founders as an essential element of the system they created.
<P>
With such strong public support for these two issues, why has there been so little action in the 104th Congress? What the public is still looking for is some measure of results, which are not yet apparent. The bottom line is that term limits and the balanced budget amendment - the two issues most popular with the American people in November, 1994 - have not yet passed. Those failures are symbols in the voters' minds of "business as usual" in Washington.
<P>
What went wrong? This book is an in-depth investigation into the politics of self preservation that have derailed the two most important reform initiatives in Congress. With a quick read, it becomes clear that the major opponents to the term limits and balanced budget amendments are Congressmen and women who are unwilling to sever their ties with Washington or release their grasp on the purse strings of the Nation.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/abic/ftb/">Footing the Bill</a> - <a href="/abic/ptf/">Pointing the Finger</a> - <a href="/abic/sbg/welcome.html.cgi">Spotlight on Big Government</a><br>
