<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Congressional Welfare Kings and Queens</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<a href="/abic/top.map">
<img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" 
ALT="Americans Back in Charge" ISMAP></a><p>


<P>

 <B><h2><CENTER>TAKING CONGRESS OFF WELFARE</h2></B>
<p>
<table border=1><tr><td>
<I><FONT SIZE=4>Isn't it time for the government to encourage
work rather than 
<br>
rewarding dependency? </FONT></I>
<FONT SIZE=4>--Contract
with America</td></tr></table></center>
<bR>
</FONT>
<P>
During the first 100 days of the 104th Congress,
the House of Representatives took up the issue of welfare reform.
 The legislation was aimed at ending welfare recipients' cycle
of lifetime dependence on the federal government and eradicating
the notion of being entitled to the receipt of a government check.


<P>
The week following the vote on welfare reform, the
House of Representatives voted against limiting their own dependency
on government checks.  Unfortunately, too many members of Congress
fail to see that they themselves have become dependent on their
own government program:  their careers in Congress.  Too many
members of Congress have come to believe that they are entitled
to their congressional seats and all the benefits they have created
along with it.

<P>
Congress has created for itself a welfare system
complete with salaries greater than those of the vast majority
of their constituents, pension programs that are far more lavish
than those of most private pension plans -- and other special
privileges that have resulted in scandalous and egregious breaches
of the public trust.

<P>
<I>The perks, pay and pension plans of the congressional
welfare system may be the real reason term limits didn't pass.

</I>
<P>
Let's compare two notorious examples of the abuse
created by the congressional welfare system--the &quot;midnight
payraise&quot; of 1989 and the House Banking Scandal of 1992--and
their effect on the vote on term limits.

<P>
While the congressional &quot;midnight payraise&quot;
was approved more than five years ago, there are 124 members who
voted for it still serving in the House of Representatives.  And
despite the public outrage at the abuses of the 1992 House banking
scandal, there are 144 House members still in office who were
revealed to have bounced checks.  These noteworthy episodes in
congressional history still linger.

<P>
And how did these Members of Congress vote on the
issue of term limits?  Not surprisingly, 71 percent of those members
who voted for the payraise and 61 percent of those members who
bounced checks opposed term limits.

<P>
All-in-all, there are 60 members of the House of
Representatives that have the dubious distinction of having all
three in common: they all voted to raise their congressional salaries,
they all bounced checks in the House bank scandal and they all
voted against term limits.  These are the reigning congressional
&quot;welfare kings and queens&quot;.

<P>
These 12 Republicans and 48 Democrats are the remnants
of the inside-Washington belief that receiving a government paycheck
is a lifetime entitlement.  Their dependence on the federal government
makes them unwilling and unable to limit congressional terms;
they are thoroughly opposed to ending congressional welfare as
they know it.

<P>
The congressional welfare kings and queens have pension
benefits worth an average of $1.73 million each.  These career
politicians have been in Congress for an average of 17.7 years.
 And they bounced an average of 86 checks each at the House bank.
 There is no better example of the need for term limits than these
career politicians building toward a cozy retirement.<BR>

<P>
The American people have said in clear and loud terms
that congressional checks are like welfare checks: they are okay
for a while but no one should get them for life.  It is time to
tell these members to get off the public dole and send them back
home to live and work under the laws they create.  It's time to
tell these Members of Congress to &quot;get a life.&quot;

<P>
The obstinate refusal of these Congressmen and women
to listen to the public will and behave accordingly is what keeps
Congress from making the changes the American people are demanding.
 These are the Members standing in the way of returning the federal
government to the role envisioned by the Founding Fathers.  As
long as these people are in Congress, the true change sought by
the voters in November 1994 will be never be realized.

<hr>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>TABLE I.<BR>
