<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Patterns in Corporate Philanthropy VIII: Notes and Methodology -- CRC</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<ul>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-pcp.gif">
</center>
<img src="/crc/images/pcpmeth.gif" alt="Methodology & Notes">
<P>

	Capital Research Center wrote to each of the 250 largest American corporations (as ranked by <I>Forbes</I> according to sales) and requested information on both direct corporate and corporate foundation charitable contributions, including a complete list of grant amounts and recipients for 1992.  We obtained partial or complete lists of grant recipients from 147 corporations.  (These lists included data on giving by the corporation, its subsidiaries, and/or its corporate foundation.  The structure of each corporate program determined the nature of the lists.)  The 147 corporate responses included ten lists of direct corporate grants only, 110 lists of corporate foundation grants only, and nine lists of both corporate foundation and direct corporate grants.  Another 18 lists lacked the data necessary to determine a company rating. (In some cases the company did not have a philanthropic program, or no grants to advocacy groups were found, or the grant recipients were listed without corresponding dollar amounts).  While most scholarly studies consider data samples of 5-10% a success, we obtained sufficient data to establish giving patterns for 51.6% of the <I>Forbes</I> 250.
<P>
	Each corporate foundation is required to file a Form 990-PF annually with the Internal Revenue Service.  The form lists grant recipients and the amounts awarded to each.  We obtained copies of these forms from the Foundation Center or from companies directly.  In Section Two, citation of a Form 990-PF as the only available data source indicates that the company did not provide independent information for its direct giving or that of its subsidiaries.  In these cases the list of grant recipients represents only those grants made through the corporate foundation.  Capital Research Center made at least two follow-up telephone calls when a corporation failed to send requested information, or sent only partial information after three requests.
<P>	In addition to all non-advocacy related grants, we generally excluded three types of giving: &quot;in kind&quot; contributions such as land or computer equipment, because data are not readily available; grants matching gifts from company employees, because employees generally determine the choice of recipient; and contributions to political action committees, because grants to candidates are fundamentally different from nonprofit advocacy giving.
<P>	After a careful review of annual reports, newsletters, books, pamphlets, and other relevant publications, Capital Research Center classified over 300 grant recipients, using an eight-point scale: 1 (radical left), 2 (left), 3 (liberal), 4 (center-left), 5 (center), 6 (center-right), 7 (market liberal), 8 (conservative).  	Ratings were based on primary source information and reputable secondary sources.  Evaluators worked separately to assure independent analyses of the documentation, and individual group ratings were averaged to determine each organization's final rating.  Although this process is judgemental, similar category and rating systems are common in social science and public policy research measuring the impact of ideology on public policy.
<P>	To analyze the giving patterns of each corporation and, where applicable, its foundation, we computed a mean from the ratings assigned to each corporate grant recipient, <I>adjusted </I>by the dollar amount of each grant.  The company rating, then, is a weighted average of its recipients' ratings.  For example, if a company makes 10 grants to public affairs organizations, 9 for $1,000 each and 1 for $50,000, with all $1,000 grants awarded to conservative groups (rated 8) and the $50,000 grant to a group with a rating of 2 (left), the adjusted mean is 2.9 * ([{9 * (8 * $1,000)} + {2 * $50,000}] / [{9 * $1,000} + $50,000]) because the corporation gave far more in dollar terms to leftist than to conservative groups.
<P>	Thus, the corporate rating is a computation and letter grades were derived from this figure for every corporation giving at least $250,000 to nonprofit advocacy groups.  Based on ratings of 8 and 7 for change-oriented right, 6 for establishment-right, 5 for nonideological, 4 and 3 for establishment-left, and 2 and 1 for change-oriented left groups, an adjusted mean of at least 6.5 merits an &quot;A;&quot; an adjusted mean of 5.5 to 6.4, a &quot;B;&quot; an adjusted mean of 4.5 to 5.4, a &quot;C;&quot; an adjusted mean of 3.0 to 4.4, a &quot;D;&quot; and an adjusted mean below 3.0, an &quot;F.&quot;  A corporation that consistently supported nonprofit advocacy groups that favor reducing regulatory barriers to enterprise would thus easily merit an &quot;A,&quot; while one that supported nonideological groups or that contributed equally to groups of both the left and right would receive a &quot;C.&quot;

<P>	Grades refer only to corporate contributions to nonprofit advocacy groups that attempt to influence public policy.  Giving to museums, symphonies, medical research and education institutions, and organizations that primarily provide direct services to the poor is not counted.  For complete profiles of all of corporations, or for an alphabetical list of principal recipient groups, <a href="mailto:info@crc.org">contact Capital Research Center</a> for a copy of the latest report, <I>Patterns in Corporate Philanthropy IX</I>.
<P><br>
<h3>Notes</h3>

<small>
1. See Stuart Nolan and Gregory P. Conko, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: Executive Hypocrisy</I>, Studies in Philanthropy #15 (1993); Marvin Olasky, Daniel T. Oliver, and Stuart Nolan, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: The Progressive Deception</I>, Studies in Philanthropy #12 (1992); Marvin Olasky, Daniel T. Oliver, and Robert V. Pambianco, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: Funding False Compassion</I>, Studies in Philanthropy #9 (1991); Thomas J. DiLorenzo, Daniel T. Oliver, and Robert E. Winters, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: The &quot;Suicidal Impulse,&quot;</I> Studies in Philanthropy #7 (1990); James T. Bennett, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: Ideas, Advocacy, and the Corporation</I>, Studies in Philanthropy #5 (1989); Roger E. Meiners and David N. Laband, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: Public Affairs Giving and the Forbes 250</I>, Studies in Philanthropy #4 (1988); and Marvin Olasky, <I>Patterns of Corporate Philanthropy: Public Affairs Giving and the Forbes 100</I>, Studies in Philanthropy #3 (Washington: Capital Research Center, 1987).
<BR>	2. For a more detailed explanation of &quot;progressive philanthropy,&quot; see Daniel T. Oliver, &quot;`Progressive' or Regressive Philanthropy?,&quot; <I>Alternatives in Philanthropy</I>, October 1991, pp.1-6.
<BR>	3. For more information on priveleges enjoyed by Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, see Stu Nolan, &quot;Fannie Mae Supports Leftism With Taxpayers' Money,&quot; <I>Human Events</I>, April 8, 1994.
<BR>	4. For further discussion of the morality of corporate philanthropy, see Willa Johnson, &quot;Freedom and Philanthropy: An Interview with Milton Friedman,&quot; <I>Alternatives in Philanthropy</I>, March 1989, pp.1-6.
<BR>	5. For more information on Children's Defense Fund, see: Robert V. Pambianco, &quot;CDF: Power, Influence &amp; Access in the Clinton Administration,&quot; <I>Organization Trends</I>, August 1993, pp.1-4, &quot;CDF's Radical Agenda and the Hillary Connection,&quot; <I>Human Events</I>, February 27, 1993, pp.10,11, and &quot;In the Name of Children,&quot; <I>Organization Trends</I>, April 1992, pp.1-4; and William T. Poole, &quot;Children's Defense Fund,&quot; <I>Profile</I>, July 1987, pp.1-22.
</small>
<P>
</body>
