<TITLE>October 1996:  Alternatives in Philanthropy</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="O" align="left" ISMAP></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ap.gif"><br>
</center>
<P>
<I>October 1996</I><BR>
<h2>College Accreditation</h2>
<hr>
<h3>The Resurgence of Academic Excellence</h3><BR>
<FONT  SIZE=+1>By Dr. Patrick G.D. Riley</FONT></B><BR>
<p>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=15 CELLSPACING=10>
<tr><td width=4000 valign="left">
<UL>
<LI><a href="#1">College Accredidation</a><br>
<LI><a href="#2">How Accrediting Works</a><br>
<LI><a href="#3">From Academic Standards to "Diversity Standards</a><br>
<LI><a href="#4">Baruch College</a><br>
<LI><a href="#5">Westminster Theological Seminary</a><BR>
<LI><a href="#6">Thomas Aquinas College</a><BR>
<LI><a href="#7">Other Ways of Ensuring Excellence?</a><br>                     
<LI><a href="#8">How Alumni Associations Can Help</a><BR>
</UL>
</td>
<td>
<BR>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><P>
<FONT  SIZE=+1>Terrence Scanlon, Publisher</FONT>
<P>
<B>Capital Research Center</B> is a nonpartisan education and research organization
<BR>classified by the IRS as a 501(c)(3) public charity.
<P>
<B>CRC</B>, 727 15th Street, NW, Suite 800, Washington, DC, 20005 (202) 393-2600  
<A HREF="http://www.capitalresearch.org">http://www.capitalresearch.org</A>
<BR>
</FONT>
</tr>
</table>
<table>
<tr>
<td colspan=2>
<CENTER><P>
<BR>
<B><FONT  SIZE=+1>For more information, contact:</B><BR></FONT></CENTER></td>
<tr>
<td>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B>The American Academy for Liberal Education
</B><BR>1015 Eighteenth Street, NW, Suite 204
<BR>Washington, DC 20036
<BR>(202) 452-8611
<P></FONT>
</td>
<td valign=top>
<FONT  SIZE=-1><B>The National Alumni Forum</B>
<BR>1625 K Street, NW, Suite 310
<BR>Washington, DC 20006
<BR>(202) 467-6787<BR>
</FONT>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<a name="1">
<HR>
<BR>
<DD>Almost out of public sight, a struggle for the future of higher education has reached a crisis point. The outcome of that crisis is still uncertain. At stake is whether colleges and universities should retain their wide institutional variety, unique to American higher education, or become standardized instruments for social change.
<P>For two decades, ideology-driven academics have sought to shape higher education to reflect their "politically correct" views. They have won some battles but lost others, largely because some few college administrators have held firm and because the Department of Education and Congress have intervened.
<P>
<a name="2">
<B>How Accrediting Works</B>
<P>
College accreditation is a little-understood cooperative process. Reminiscent of the medieval guild system, it is essentially peer review, designed to ensure quality among institutions of higher learning. It amounts to an endorsement of one school by representatives of other schools.
<P>
The U.S. Department of Education recognizes six tax-exempt 501(c)(3)
regional accrediting associations. They are the Middle States Associatioin of Colleges nad Schools Commission on Higher Education (Philadelphia), New England Association of Schools and Colleges Commission on Institutions of Higher Education (Bedford, Massachusetts), North Central Association of Colleges and Schools
Commission on Institutions of Higher Education (Chicago), Northwest Association of Schools & Colleges (Seattle), Southern Association of Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges (decatur, Georgia), and Western Association of Schools and Colleges Accrediting Commission for Senior Colleges and Universities (Oakland, California). Each accredits schools in its respective region. Middle States, for example, accredits colleges,
secondary schools, and elementary schools in Delaware, the District of Columbia, Maryland, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Puerto Rico, the Republic of Panama, and the Virgin Islands.
<P>
Accrediting agencies derive their budgets primarily from dues from member schools,
although workshop and consulting fees, publication sales, and foundation 
support supplement these revenues.  The boards of  accrediting agencies are generally composed of representatives from member schools.  The creation of new accrediting 
standards usually requires input from member institutions.
<P>
<a name="3">
<P><B>From Academic Standards to &quot;Diversity Standards&quot;</B>
<P>
Educators began banding together to create accrediting agencies in the late 19th century out of fear that the federal government would standardize higher education.  
After World War II, the federal government began to rely 
on accrediting associations to guarantee quality education 
to veterans attending college under the GI Bill of Rights.  
Only accredited schools could receive GI students using 
federal funds to pay for tuition.  Accreditors were thus 
made gatekeepers of federal monies, a role that expanded 
substantially as federal funding of higher education in the 
form of student loans and research grants increased.  By 
the 1970s, accreditors held life-or-death funding power 
over most colleges and universities.
<P>
Emboldened by the political correctness movement 
of the 1980s, some accrediting agencies--particularly 
Middle States and the Western Association of Schools and 
Colleges--began to look beyond traditional accrediting 
criteria, such as library resources, laboratory equipment, 
and classroom space.  &quot;Diversity standards&quot; began to 
overshadow longstanding academic standards.  These 
newer standards essentially sought to tell colleges and 
universities what they should teach, who should teach it, and to 
whom it should be taught.  Some colleges and universities 
even gave accreditors an important role in recruiting and 
hiring faculty and administrators, whose decisions often 
revolved around the open-sesame words &quot;diversity&quot; and 
&quot;affirmative action.&quot;
<P>
Some colleges balked at the new standards.  &quot;You 
will destroy us,&quot; the dean of St. John's College, a small 
liberal arts college in Annapolis, Maryland, wrote to Middle States. 
 As a result of complaints from other schools under 
Middle States' jurisdiction, the Department of Education in 
1991 temporarily withheld reauthorization of Middle 
States' accrediting powers.
<P>
On June 22, 1990, Middle States told the Department 
of Education that although it had referred to &quot;equity 
and diversity concerns&quot; in 221 letters to colleges and 
universities over the last ten years, in only two cases had 
such concerns become problematic.  These, Middle 
States claimed, were &quot;satisfactorily resolved.&quot;
<P>
Yet college and university officials estimate that 
roughly one out of three campus visits by accrediting teams 
still raises questions regarding the &quot;diversity&quot; of curricula or 
of students, faculty, and trustees.  No one can say for sure 
how many colleges and universities have had accreditation delayed due to an alleged failure to meet diversity standards.  Schools are reluctant to draw attention to problems 
in obtaining accreditation for fear that students, 
graduates, and donors will question an institution's adequacy.  
Furthermore, college administrators do not want to attract 
the wrath of accreditors.
<P>
Some observers say that accreditors have recently 
placed renewed emphasis on traditional academic standards.  
But diversity standards have causedand continue to 
causesubstantial problems for colleges and universities.
<P>
<a name="4">
<P><B>Baruch College</B>
<P>
In an October 29, 1990 op-ed piece in the <I>Wall 
Street Journal</I>, Dr. Joel Segall, former president of Bernard 
Baruch College, a highly-esteemed business school of the 
City University of New York, wrote that the Middle 
States Association of Colleges and Schools was subjecting 
Baruch to &quot;a Kafkaesque trial process.&quot;  Segall claimed that 
institutions evaluated by Middle States &quot;are not made aware 
of explicit charges nor are they presented with evidence.&quot;
<P>
Speaking in November the following year at a meeting 
of the U.S. Department of Education's Committee on 
Accreditation, Segall said: &quot;During the lengthy 
discussions with Middle States' representatives prior to the visit of 
the evaluation team, there was absolutely no suggestion that 
the proportions of minority faculty and administrators 
and retention rates [of minority students] would play a role 
in the accreditation.&quot;  He added that when these demands 
were later put before him, he was &quot;blindsided.&quot;  At the 
time, Baruch's student body was 36 percent white, 26 
percent black, 20 percent Asian, and 18 percent Hispanic.  
Minorities comprised 18 percent of full-time facultyfar 
higher than most colleges in the country.
<P>
&quot;Persuaded that an unfortunate mistake had been 
made,&quot; Segall met with Dr. Howard L. Simmons, the executive director of Middle States.  Segall &quot;had barely started&quot; 
to present figures showing the diversity already present 
at Baruch when Simmons stopped him, remarking 
ironically, &quot;I don't want to get into a numbers game with you.&quot;  
After some discussion, Segall finally asked Simmons what 
he wanted.  Simmons responded with two words: 
&quot;Social justice.&quot;  From that, Segall concluded that Middle 
States' was motivated by &quot;zealotry in pursuit of what is 
essentially a political agenda and a social goal.&quot;
<P>
Baruch College was reaccredited after it developed 
a comprehensive plan to hire more minority faculty 
and administrators.  But Segall claimed it &quot;was a cave-in. . . , and for that I am responsible.&quot;  When the <I>New York Times</I> ran a front page story on the affair, corporate donors began to pull back, parents expressed concern, and students 
feared that federal loans would dry up.  &quot;We fielded a lot 
of telephone calls from alumni asking whether their 
degree really meant anything any more,&quot; Segall said.  He 
eventually resigned.
<P>
<a name="5">
<P><B>Westminster Theological Seminary</B>
<P>
On April 1, 1989, the dean of Westminster 
Theological Seminary in Pennsylvania responded to a concern 
expressed by Middle States regarding the all-male 
membership of Westminster's board.  The seminary's 
constitution, the dean explained, required that the governing 
board consist of ordained elders, and the seminary 
understood Scripture to forbid the ordination of women.  On March 
7, 1990, Middle States, declaring that it would not 
&quot;compromise&quot; on &quot;principles,&quot; ordered Westminster to show 
cause &quot;why its accreditation should not be removed.&quot;
<P>
Middle States executive director Howard Simmons 
was summoned in November 1990 to the Department of 
Education to discuss his request for renewed recognition 
of Middle States' accrediting authority.  Simmons 
claimed that diversity &quot;is not something which was required by us.&quot; 
 But the Department's Committee on Accreditation was 
not convinced, and recommended remanding Middle 
States' accrediting powers.  In April the new Secretary of 
Education, Lamar Alexander, sent the matter to the 
Advisory Committee for fresh scrutiny.  Simmons and his 
backers would have to explain themselves again the 
following November.
<P>
But even before Secretary Alexander ordered 
recognition withheld, Middle States compromised 
with Westminster: women would serve on committees of 
the seminary's board, though not on the board itself.  
The compromise came after Middle States was chastised in 
a resounding legal opinion by veteran First 
Amendment litigator William Bentley Ball, appealing on 
Westminster's behalf to the Council on Postsecondary Accreditation, 
a now-defunct Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit that 
oversaw regional accreditors.  After the compromise, 
Middle States revoked its show-cause order and asked 
Westminster to withdraw its complaints to the Department of Education.
But the attempt of Middle States to save face ran into 
a stone wall November 20, 1991 at the meeting of the 
Department of Education's Committee on Accreditation.  
The Committee was armed with a staff report 
contradicting Middle States' claim to Secretary Alexander: that 
since 1981, only two cases dealing with diversity had 
become problematicBaruch and Westminster.  Twenty cases 
selected from the files at the Department of Education 
showed that Middle States had &quot;increased the level of 
enforcement of its diversity standards,&quot; that it had &quot;treated these 
standards as mandatory,&quot; and that it had &quot;repeatedly used 
the threat of non-accreditation to obtain compliance.&quot;
<P>
Within a month of this meeting, the trustees of 
Middle States voted not to apply &quot;diversity&quot; to Westminster or 
to any school as a condition of accreditation.  But 
according to the <I>Chronicle of Higher 
Education</I>, senior staff at Middle States said they &quot;were only clarifying their position&quot; 
and that they &quot;still supported the diversity standards, but 
had never intended to use them to deny accreditation to 
colleges.&quot;  Early in February 1992, the Department of 
Education renewed its recognition of Middle States' 
accrediting authority.
<P>
<a name="6">
<P><B>Thomas Aquinas College</B>
<P>
In late 1993, <I>The Wall Street Journal</I> opined that 
&quot;Anyone who still believes that political correctness is an 
imagined threat should have a look at what a university 
accrediting body is proposing in California. . . .  [The 
Western Association of Schools and Colleges] is now proposing 
that schools meet a new `diversity' standard, arguing that 
`diversity is an essential element of academic discipline. . . .' 
 WASC executive director Dr. Stephen Weiner (who did 
not return calls) has announced that diversity is 
`inextricably linked' to `quality' in higher education.  In short, unless 
a school shows that it subscribes to this suddenly 
discovered dogma, WASC's accreditors would not consider it a 
school that could provide a quality education.&quot;
<P>
Why would WASC venture into waters where Middle States almost met shipwreck?  The answer is probably twofold: the arrival of the Clinton Administration 
and former Stanford University president Donald 
Kennedy's support of WASC.  Unlike Baruch and Westminster, 
on whose behalf Bush Education Secretary Lamar 
Alexander intervened, Clinton Education Secretary Richard 
Riley took no action regarding Thomas Aquinas College, a 
small Catholic liberal arts college in California.
<P>
Thomas Aquinas College was founded 25 years ago 
to steep students in the traditions of Western Culture.  
During one visit, representatives of WASC asked 
then-president Dr. Ronald MacArthur why the school didn't teach African philosophy.  He responded that it would do so if 
WASC could suggest an African philosopher up to the level of 
the philosophers the college was already teaching.
<P>
WASC reaccredited Thomas Aquinas in 1993, but 
WASC executive director Stephen Weiner was not fully satisfied. 
 &quot;Thomas Aquinas is a good institution of its 
particular kind,&quot; Weiner said.  &quot;I think it would be a better 
institution if it were more concerned with a variety of cultural 
institutions.&quot;
<P>
At the time, Weiner was seeking approval from 
WASC accredited institutions for his &quot;Policy Statement on 
Diversity,&quot; then in its third draft.  Since 1991, Thomas 
Aquinas had criticized the drafts, which included such 
dubious assertions as &quot;All study is intended to break down 
narrow certainties.&quot;  Drafts of the statement also lacked any 
guarantee that WASC would not punish institutions found 
deficient in &quot;diversity.&quot;  A majority of WASC-accredited 
institutions supported the statement by January 1994, 
though many of their letters of support were guarded.  
Opponents also charged that some institutions acted out of fear 
of retribution from WASC.
<P>But by this time, a second issue had moved to the fore. 
 WASC demanded that universities strike a better 
balance between the time teachers spent teaching and the time 
they devoted to research.  This encroached on the turf of 
some powerful people, including new Stanford University 
president Gerhard Casper, who had already been considering 
the problems that research poses for teaching.  He and 
others resented WASC's intrusion into dilemmas they were 
seeking to resolve themselves.
<P>In early 1994, Casper, addressing the Stanford 
Faculty Senate, acknowledged his own liberal political 
convictions, but he drew a clear distinction between means 
and ends: &quot;A university must prize freedom, 
nondiscrimination and equality of opportunity for every university 
citizen above all other values.  But it is a serious mistake to 
believe that such values are promoted by layers of 
bureaucratic regulation.&quot;  The Faculty Senate voted to endorse 
Casper's opposition to WASC's diversity statement, and it 
added that WASC &quot;has circulated a second policy draft [on 
teaching and research] that is more troubling than the 
diversity statement.&quot;
<P>Casper declared, &quot;I will do everything possible to 
resist this kind of intrusion on the part of an outside agency.&quot;  
He intimated how: &quot;New federal regulations have begun 
to transfer some of the traditional functions of 
accrediting groups to state agencies.  While I would normally 
oppose more government oversight, in this case the state may do 
a better job than WASC has done recently.&quot;
<P>But Weiner's confidence was not shaken.  He had 
garnered a show of support for his diversity statement and 
had the backing of the chairman of the accrediting 
commission of WASC, Dr. Donald Gerth.  Weiner's confidence 
might have been justified if his only worry had been WASC.  
But he was also seeking to create a national group that 
would accredit accrediting associations.  This effort fell 
apart amid criticism that it was a power grab.
<P>Weiner abruptly left on a three-month paid leave 
in March of 1994.  On March 17, a rump group of 
disgruntled WASC members met at Pepperdine University and 
laid plans for a meeting of WASC that April in Maui, 
Hawaii (which is under WASC's jurisdiction).  Their carefully 
laid strategyto discredit WASC policiesprevailed.  
The Maui meeting turned into a rebellion against the old regime. 
 Dr. Gerth and others admitted that the credibility of 
WASC had suffered.
<P>
On May 5, 1994, Attorney Ball entered the WASC dispute on behalf of Thomas Aquinas.  He told WASC that its attempt to force &quot;diversity and multiculturalism&quot; 
on institutions of higher learning infringed their First 
Amendment rights.  His 20-page opinion went unanswered, as 
had a briefer memo to the same effect from Michael 
McConnell, a prominent professor at the University of Chicago 
Law School.
<P>By this time, Gerth had apparently realized that he 
might find himself presiding over the dissolution of WASC. 
 Weiner's assistant, Ralph Wolff, announced that a 
meeting of the accrediting commission of WASC, scheduled 
for June 23, 1994 and open to representatives of accredited institutions, would discuss &quot;the future of WASC.&quot;  
The announcement was taken to imply that the policies 
anathema to Stanford and other universities could become a 
dead letter.
<P>
That fall another storm broke.  A provision of the 
WASC constitution that had been designed to protect the 
autonomy of accredited institutions, especially those under 
religious sponsorship, was surreptitiously altered.  Questions 
of good faith arose.  Weiner showed a reluctance to 
produce minutes of meetings of the accrediting commission 
during which the amendment was made, and Gerth, under 
pressure, provided an explanation that proved inaccurate.  
In May of 1995, Weiner's resignation was announced, 
effective in July of 1996.
<P>
<a name="7">
<P><B>Other Ways of Ensuring Excellence?</B>
<P>
Yet many problems remain.  The plan for a 
national supervising board of accreditors has, at least for 
now, failed.  In place of it and its predecessor, the Council 
on Postsecondary Accreditation, a group of presidents 
and trustees of accredited institutions was formed this May. 
 Calling itself the Council for Higher Education 
Accreditation, it is considered far less dangerous than a 
supervisory board of accreditors because it consists chiefly of 
college presidents.  Proponents believe it will carry weight 
with Congress in the great unsettled question of whether 
governmental accreditation should replace voluntary 
accreditation.
<P>
Some of the most prominent figures in higher 
education believe regional accreditors should play a far more 
limited role.  Professor Diane Ravitch of New York University, 
a former Department of Education assistant secretary, 
argues that accreditors &quot;should visit only schools that are in 
trouble,and leave the others alone.&quot;  Moreover, she wants 
the federal government to &quot;extend recommendation to a 
variety of accrediting groups whose purposes differ. . . .  The 
point is to break the monopoly power of the regional 
accrediting agencies and to give colleges and universities the 
opportunity to choose the kind of agency they wish to belong to 
and be judged by.&quot;
<P>
One such organization is the new American Academy 
for Liberal Education (AALE), a 501(c)(3) nonprofit based 
in Washington, D.C.  Last year, the Department of 
Education recognized AALE as national accrediting agency for 
liberal arts colleges and programs.  Concerned about 
increasing politicization on college campuses, AALE seeks to 
raise academic standards and strengthen the general 
education component of undergraduate education.  Its founding 
group of scholars and academics includes Jacques Barzun 
(Provost Emeritus of Columbia University), John Agresto 
(President of St. John's College of Santa Fe), and 
Gertrude Himmelfarb (Professor Emeritus of the City University 
of New York).
<P>
AALE President Dr. Jeffrey Wallin, former Director 
of General Programs at the National Endowment for the 
Humanities, notes that because of AALE's rigorous 
standards, which include mandatory courses in literature, 
science, and a foreign language, the number of 
institutions accredited by AALE is not expected to surpass that of regional accrediting associations.  And although the 
AALE draws its membership from a national pool, it does 
not expect to be a fierce competitor of regional accreditors. 
 Colleges that receive AALE accreditation have the 
option of declaring AALE their primary accreditor or of 
holding membership with both the AALE and their 
regional accreditor.  Thomas Aquinas College, for example, 
has applied to AALE for accreditation, but intends to 
remain within WASC.
<P>
According to its newsletter, over 150 institutions 
have contemplated AALE membership.  So far, AALE has 
granted candidacy for accreditation to three institutions and 
one program: the University of Dallas, Rhodes College 
(Memphis), Thomas Aquinas College, and the James 
Madison College of Michigan State University.  The 
accrediting process takes about a year to complete and includes:
<UL>
<LI>A self-study by the institution
<LI>An on-site visit by a team of volunteer 
	evaluators appointed by the AALE in cooperation with the school
<LI>A team report and recommendation by AALE's Council of Scholars, a body responsible 	for creating and maintaining AALE's evaluation standards
<LI>A vote by AALE's Board of Trustees
</UL>
<P>
<a name="8">
<P><B>How Alumni Associations Can Help</B>
<P>
In the controversy surrounding accreditation, one 
group appears to have been left out: parents.  True, in this age 
of federal funding, parents don't always directly foot most 
of the bill for their children's education.  Still, many 
make sacrifices to assure the best education for their offspring. 
 Moreover, they retain moral responsibility for 
their children's education, and hence should have a certain say 
in it.  Despite this, the responsibilities and rights of parents 
are rarely encountered in the literature of accreditation, 
let alone in the polemics over university curricula.
<P>
One way parents can remain involved in higher 
education is through alumni associations.  These, however, are 
often under the control of universities.  For example, 
when Thomas Troy, an historian and a graduate of Holy 
Cross College in Worcester, Massachusetts, asked his alma 
mater for the addresses of his classmates so that he could write 
to them about his objections to proposed changes in 
the college's mission statement, the president of Holy 
Cross refused.  Episodes such as this are not uncommon.
<P>
The National Alumni Forum (NAF), a 501(c)(3) 
organization based in Washington, D.C., was founded in 1995 
to support academic freedom and excellence and to enlist 
the help of alumni, donors, and trustees in the fight 
against political correctness.  With members from over 200 
colleges and universities, its leadership includes former 
National Endowment for the Humanities chairman Lynne 
V. Cheney (chairman), former Colorado Governor Richard 
D. Lamm (vice-chairman), and Jerry L. Martin (president).
<P>Working with its major donors, NAF recently created 
a program called the Fund for Academic Renewal that 
helps alumni selectively target their gifts and ensure that 
their wishes are implemented.  According to Martin, &quot;Many alumni have come to understand that unrestricted gifts to 
[a college's] annual fund can be used to support the 
mediocre as well as the excellent, the political as well as the 
academic, the trendy as well as the enduring.&quot;  Another 
new project is the Alumni and Trustees for Higher 
Education Accountability (ATHENA), which offers trustees 
advice on how to fulfill their responsibilities with an eye 
toward improving the academic quality of their institutions.  
NAF has also alerted trustees to accreditation issues and 
encouraged them to meet with the staff of the American 
Academy for Liberal Education.
<P>
Higher education, of course, has become big 
business and federal funding of colleges and universities has 
increased enormously.  Where tax money mixes with 
religion and where longstanding academic principles 
encounter new political ideologies, there is always tension and 
the danger of explosion.  Hence, the fierce struggles 
over access to alumni lists, over the academic canon, over 
the &quot;climate&quot; on campusand over accreditation.
<P>
We now have in the West a vast system for educating 
our children.  Trustees and alumni are impressed by 
splendid campuses, and fundraisers urge them to contribute to 
new building programs.  In some sense, this disguises the 
struggle for the minds of the next generation that occurs on 
college campuses.  Amid this struggle, we cannot afford to 
lose sight of the purpose of education, summed up two and a 
half millennia ago by Plato, who recalled of his own 
teacher, Socrates, that Heaven descended on his low-roofed 
cottage.<BR>
<br><P>
<BR>
<P>
<I><B>Patrick G.D. Riley</B> teaches classical antiquity at Concordia University of Wisconsin.  He holds a doctorate in 
political philosophy from the Pontifical University of St. 
Thomas Aquinas in Rome.</I>
</BODY>
