<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>October 1996 -- Organization Trends</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar"
border="O" align="left" ismap></a>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/crc/images/hdr-ot.gif">
</center>
<I>October 1996</I>
<p><center>
<h2><BR>
American Bar Association  
<I>By One Vote Lawyers' Group Picks 
Controversial President-Elect </I>
Orlando Convention Features Liberal Line Up</h2><BR>
</center>
<p>
During the first week of August, the American Bar Association
(ABA) held its annual meeting at Walt Disney World in Orlando, Florida.
Speakers included prominent Clinton administration officials suach as U.N
Ambassador Madeleine K. Albright, Attorney General Janet Reno, and Defense
Secretary William Perry. First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton received an 
award from the Young Lawyers Division. Other speakers included Supreme
Court Justice John Paul Stevens, who anchors the high court's four-man
liberal wing, and attorney Johnnie Cochran of O.J. Simpson fame.
There were no conservative speakers and no Republican politicians.
<P>
During the meeting, the Commission on Women in the Profession conferred its 
Margaret Brent Women Lawyers of Achievement Award on ultrafeminist Rep.
Patricia Schroeder (D-CO). Other recipients included liberal Judge
Rosemary Barkett, infamous for her solicitude toward violent criminal
defendants and death row inmates, and lynn Hecht Schafran, director
of the National Judicial Education Program for the NOW Legal Defense and Education
Fund. Beginning to get the picture?
<P>
The group adopted resolutions opposing term limits for judges, encouraging initiatives
that allow "extended contact visitation" between incarcerated parents and their 
children, and recommending early release for prisoners with AIDS.
<P>
The group also chose its next president-elect, Jerome Shestack, a liberal
activist whose selection does not augur well for those interested in reform.
It suggests that the ABA's leftward advance will 
only pick up speed, and that the group will involve itself in politics to an even 
greater degree.
<P>All this is further evidence of the once-prestigious ABA's descent from 
proud professional organization to political pressure group.  From its controversial role 
in the Bork battle to its support for a raft of left wing policy prescriptions, the 
ABA has lost all claim to be an unbiased voice of the legal profession.  It has become 
just another Washington lobby  not much different from the National 
Education Association, except for the more expensive suits.
<P>Yet one should not simply waive off the ABA as a lost cause and forget about it. 
The Association remains extremely influential both in the legal community, in 
law schools, and on Capitol Hill.  It continues to play a semi-official, and key, role in 
the selection of federal judges.  Its membership constitutes a powerful and 
prestiguous force in society.  And its ability to 
effect public policy can not be overstated.
<P>Thus, the ABA is something that should concern us all.  Particularly so because 
its armor is beginning to weaken.  Republican presidential candidate Robert Dole 
has made the ABA's partisanship a campaign issue.  Earlier this year, the Senate 
Judiciary Committee held a hearing to examine 
the ABA's involvement in the selection of judges.  That committee is reportedly 
one vote away from removing the ABA from the selection process.  
<P>
<P>* * * * *
<P>
<P>On issue after issue, the ABA marches in lock step with the prevailing 
liberal dogma.  It supports abortion rights and taxpayer funding of abortions, as well 
as affirmative action, gay rights, and greater gun control.  It opposes key aspects 
of welfare reform, as well as employer sanctions for immigration law violations.  
On legal issues, it follows the lead of the Association of Trial Lawyers of 
America and the contingency fee bar, opposing tort reform, caps on punitive damages in 
product liability cases, and legislation reforming federal securities law.  
<P>There are many other examples of the ABA's embrace of liberal politics.  At 
its mid-year meeting in Baltimore last February, the Association officially 
endorsed the Platform of Action adopted at the recent international women's 
conference in Beijing, China.  In addition to 
recommending the usual feminist agenda of abortion, &quot;children's rights,&quot; and 
affirmative action for women, the multilateral gathering considered measures 
recognizing &quot;five genders&quot; (male 
heterosexual, female heterosexual, gay, lesbian, and 
bisexual).  
<P>What is particularly troubling is not merely that the ABA supports liberal 
policies, but the extent to which its positions seem dictated more by the winds of 
political correctness than by sober analysis.  Consumed with issues like domestic 
violence and sexual harassment, the ABA has become a slave to liberal chic.
<P>The Association's Committee on Women in the Profession has been 
particularly busy.  Earlier this year, it released a report entitled 
<I>Elusive Equality</I>, which recommends that law schools 
establish committees on 
gender issues so that they might better meet the needs of women 
in the law school community.  The committees are supposed to monitor the 
curriculum to ensure that it is sufficiently inclusive of women's issues.  Emphasizing 
the need for more racial and sexual diversity within faculties, the report notes that
&quot;Many schools have found that they can hire better and more diverse groups of 
people if they are flexible about credentials. . . .&quot; 
 (Translation:  lowering or eliminating standards is an easy way to increase the 
pool of viable candidates.)  The report also suggests that gender issues  e.g. 
how many women are selected for law review  should be a factor in determining 
whether or not to grant accreditation to a law school.
<P><I>Elusive Equality</I> follows a 1995 report, 
<I>Unfinished Business</I>, which claims that there is widespread discrimination 
against women in law firms  and that the way to rectify this problem is to treat
women differently than men.  The report offers support for the notion that two sets 
of standards are needed to evaluate the performance of male and female 
attorneys, because &quot;Using the same criteria to 
evaluate men and women frequently undervalues the contributions of women.&quot;
<P>These reports were funded by the ABA's 
Fund for Justice and Education, the group's 501(c)(3) tax-exempt affiliate, which
receives over 40 percent of its revenues from the federal government.  For
fiscal year 1995, the Fund received $13,345,570 in federal funding.  This money 
came from various government agencies including the Departments of Justice,
Education, and Health and Human Services, the National Endowment for the 
Humanities and the U.S. Information Agency.  Other sources of support include the 
ABA, state governments, individuals, law firms, and institutional donors such as the 
Edna McConnell Clark Foundation, Weyerhauser Foundation, and Ford 
Motor Company.
<P><I>Why does an organization that claims to represent one of the wealthiest groups 
of people in society need taxpayer funding?  The ABA spends considerable amounts 
of time and money attempting to rehabilitate the image of attorneys in America.  
By refusing taxpayer money during the current budget crisis, it could take 
major steps toward achieving that goal.
<P><B>Current ABA President Lee Cooper</B></I><BR>
By involving itself so forcefully in policy issues in which it has no particular 
expertise the ABA can no longer credibly claim to the preeminent national 
representative of the legal profession.  Indeed
declining membership numbers belie such claims.  The ABA currently represents less 
than one half (37 percent) of the profession, and it should come as no surprise
that membership in the ABA has been steadily dropping.  After years of increases, 
membership has been falling throughout the nineties  from a highwater mark 
of 362,104 in 1991-92 to 333,831 in 1995-96.  Even more striking, the number 
of ABA members who are judges has dropped by over 40 percent.  Between 1988-89 
and 1995-96, the number of judicial members fell from 5,488 to 3,295.  
<P>Federal Appeals Judge John M. Walker, testifying before the Senate Judiciary 
Committee in May, noted that the politicization of the ABA creates &quot;special problems&quot; 
for judges.  According to Judge Walker, 
&quot;there is an inherent conflict between a bar association's political activity and the 
ability of judges who are members of that bar association to contribute to the 
association and at the same time to maintain the unquestioned impartiality and political 
neutrality that their judicial office requires.&quot;
<P>
<P><B>Perception versus Reality</B>
<P>The ABA bristles at charges of partisanship and argues that its political 
activities are wholly consistent with its role as a professional organization.  It regards 
the only problem as one of perception, not reality.
<P>This year Alabama attorney Lee Cooper became the ABA's president for 
1996-1997.  His selection is seen by many as an attempt to overcome the perception 
that the ABA is just another liberal special interest advocacy group.  A 
moderately conservative Southern Democrat who is pro-life, Cooper, 56, became president 
at the annual meeting in August.  He has said that the ABA should back away 
from involvement in contentious social issues that can only harm the organization.
<P>Yet Cooper's ascendancy appears to be only a hiatus from the group's 
leftward swing.  The Orlando convention demonstrated that, far from backing away 
from politics, the ABA has become even more its creature.  Rather than affirm its 
professional standing or at least move toward the center, the group remains dedicated 
to advancing the agenda of contemporary liberalism.  The selection of the 
group's next president, Jerome Shestack, signals that the activist community has no 
intention of relinquishing its grip on the ABA.
<P>
<P><B>Jerome Shestack:  The Model of a Liberal Lawyer</B>
<P>The ABA selects its presidents one year in advance.  The first step is to be 
nominated.  At the mid-year meeting in Baltimore, the ABA's nominating 
committee nominated Shestack by a one-vote margin, 31 to 30.  The nomination must 
then be approved by the House of Delegates at the annual meeting.  This vote, 
however, is largely a rubber stamp.  The current president, Cooper, was chosen at 
the ABA's convention last year, and began his term this August.  
<P>In Orlando, the House of Delegates approved the nominating 
committee's choice of Jerome Shestack to be the organizations
next president-elect. He will take over in August 1997.
<P>
A Philadelphia lawyer, Shestack stands in sharp contrast from Cooper.  A 
former executive director of the Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights under Law 
and Carter administration ambassador to the United Nations Commission on 
Human Rights, Shestack does not shy from controversy.  It is widely reported 
that Shestack was one of four minority members of the Standing Committee on 
the Judiciary who decided that Robert Bork should receive the ABA rating &quot;not 
qualified&quot; to serve on the Supreme Court.  
The split vote was exploited successfully by Bork opponents to rally opposition to 
his confirmation.
<P>Shestack also reportedly has questioned judicial nominees about their 
religious views.  Arthur Schwab, who was nominated by President Reagan to the 
Third Circuit Court of Appeals, claims that Shestack asked him about his 
family's religious practices and the enrollment of Schwab's children at a religious school. 
 Although Shestack denies the charge, Schwab credits him with scuttling 
his nomination.  According to <I>ABA Watch</I>, a publication of the Federalist Society, 
U.S. District Judge James Graham has also said that the Standing Committee, 
while Shestack was a member, asked him about his religous views during the nomination
process.
<P><I>ABA Watch</I> also reports that Shestack has been a prominent supporter of
Democratic politicians like former Senate Judiciary Committee chairman Joseph
Biden and Pennsylvania's Lynn Yeakel, founder of the nonprofit group, Women's Way.
 Yeakel made Republican Senator Arlen Specter's questioning of Anita Hill 
during the confirmation hearings for Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas the 
raison d' etre of her unsuccessful 1992 Senate campaign against Specter.  
<P>The acerbic Shestack garnered public attention in 1992 when the 
<I>Washington Post</I> reported his reaction to the 
ABA's refusal to allow then-Vice President Quayle to speak as its convention.  Shestack 
quipped that the ABA probably would have allowed Quayle to speak if he was a man 
of &quot;personal stature or legal ability.&quot; 
<P>In short, Shestack's record and statements leave no doubt about where 
he intends to lead the American Bar Association.  His selection sends a strong 
signal that the ABA has no intention to reform itself.
<P>
<P><B>Judicial Selection:  Time to Pull the Plug</B>
<P>The ABA's tarnished record in evaluating judicial appointments offers the 
most evidence of its decline as a professional organization.  Since the 1950s, the 
attorney general, prior to the nomination of federal judges, has provided the ABA 
with the names of prospective nominees.  The Association is also provided with 
background information on the candidates.  It interviews the candidates and rates 
them on a scale of well-qualified, qualified, or not qualified.  This is an awesome 
and unusual responsibility for a private organization.
<P>The Senate Judiciary Committee examined Republican and Democratic 
nominees with similar backgrounds and qualifications.  It found that Democratic 
nominees were consistently rated &quot;well qualified&quot; while similarly-situated 
Republican nominees received lower ratings.
<P>For instance, on the D.C. Circuit, liberal jurists Patricia Wald, Abner Mikva, 
and David Tatel all received &quot;well 
qualified&quot; ratings, while conservatives like 
Judges Laurence Silberman and James Buckley were given lower &quot;qualified&quot;/&quot;not 
qualified&quot; ratings. 
<P>Likewise, Seventh Circuit Democrat Diane Wood was given a 
&quot;well-qualified&quot; rating, while Judges Richard Posner 
and Frank Easterbrook, two titans of law and economics theory, both received 
qualified / not qualified ratings.  
<P>These facts have lead many to regard the ABA's evaluation process as 
fundamentally biased.  In May, the Senate Judiciary Committee held a hearing to 
examine the ABA's role in judicial selection.  
Among those testifying was Washington attorney Daniel Troy, a former Justice 
Department official who has been actively involved in several ABA
committees and working groups. Troy testified that ABA evaluations
have become "overly political" and that the ABA's Standing Committee
on the Federal Judiciary "does indeed take the political views
of nominees whose views are not consonant with the ABA's liberal
philosophy."
<p>
P>Even the <I>Washington Post</I> reported that of the 15 members of the Standing 
Committee, 11 have made political contributions  nine to Democratic 
candidates and causes.  One member, Mortimer Caplin, gave over $12,000 to 
Democrats between 1991 and 1993.  In another article, the 
<I>Post</I> noted that about 67 percent of President Clinton's nominees 
received the ABA's highest rating, as compared to 52 and 53 percent for Presidents Bush 
and Reagan, respectively.  Perhaps not surprisingly, the Clinton administration 
has defended the ABA's role in the process.
<P>The ABA and its defenders insist that critics place too much emphasis on 
its advocacy of political positions and that in no way does it preclude the 
organization from being a neutral player in the 
process of judicial selection.  The Association claims that there is a Chinese Wall 
separating the ABA's political activities from its semi-official judicial evaluation duties. 
Responding to disbelieving Senators, ABA officials insisted that the ABA's 
Standing Committee on the 
Judiciary is &quot;insulated&quot; from the ABA's policymaking
activities and &quot;conducts its work completely
independent of the rest of the ABA.&quot;  
Standing committee members &quot;leave their 
politics at the door,&quot; they claim.
<P>Yet Senators' questions revealed that the wall of separation is at best a 
flimsy partition.  Chairman Orrin Hatch (R-UT) noted that Standing Committee 
members can also serve in the ABA's House of Delegates, which is responsible for 
adopting the group's positions on public policy issues.  He also noted that the current 
staff director for the Standing Committee, Irene Emsellem, is also a senior legislative 
counsel for the ABA's lobbying arm.  Emsellem was formerly a staffer for Senator 
Edward M. Kennedy (D-MA).
<P>Notwithstanding this probe, the ABA continues to enjoy its special 
quasi-official role in the judicial selection process.  
The Clinton Administration provides it wit<BR>
h early notification of the names of nominees and special access to 
information about those nominees.  The ABA continues to be received respectfully on 
Capitol Hill, and the Republican-controlled Senate Judiciary Committee has yet to take 
action to remove the ABA from the process.  Why?
<P>* * * * *
<P>In the battle of ideas, conservatives have won many strategic victories in 
recent years.  But the control of institutions  the schools, the media, the 
academy, and foundations  remains the province of the Left.  Professional 
organizations, including the most rigorously 
specialized, have not been able to resist the long 
march through the institutions that political advocacy groups commenced in the 1960s. 
 Until the mainstream reclaims these institutions or establishes suitable 
alternatives, groups like the American Bar 
Association must be recognized for what they are.  
<P>
